00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:00.480
One of the things that was
seen, interesting study

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:02.300
that I noted at the
end the other day,

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.930
was looking at people with
amygdala lesions, Damasio

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:08.500
and his group looking at
this, keeping track of where

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:09.509
the eyes are looking.

00:02:09.509 --> 00:02:12.920
When they see another face, they
are not looking with the eyes

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:15.590
any or near as much as
everybody else would.

00:02:15.590 --> 00:02:18.670
They are instead tracking around
all sorts of extraneous parts

00:02:18.670 --> 00:02:19.530
of the face.

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:23.120
Normally, people look
at the eyes a whole lot.

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:25.460
And what that winds
up showing is not only

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:28.740
is the amygdala playing
a role in deciding

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:32.980
this is a fear or
aggression-evoking stimulus,

00:02:32.980 --> 00:02:35.140
the amygdala is also
on the lookout for it.

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:38.030
And what we will see in a little
while is one of the things

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:42.060
testosterone does is
make the amygdala better

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.380
at looking for fear and
anger-evoking faces.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:47.380
So part of what the
amygdala is doing

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:49.970
is taking in
sensory information.

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:53.511
We touched in the limbic lecture
on one interesting aspect

00:02:53.511 --> 00:02:54.010
of it.

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:58.430
OK, back to that business,
that the limbic strategy

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:01.580
of counting the number of
synapses, that strange business

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:04.670
about olfaction being
only one synapse away

00:03:04.670 --> 00:03:07.470
from lots of parts
of the limbic system,

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:09.530
including the amygdala
if you were dealing

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:12.570
with a [INAUDIBLE],
the olfactory world

00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:14.410
as being so emotional
for a rodent.

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.400
For us, we've got something
else interesting happening.

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:19.170
And I think I mentioned this.

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:21.070
OK, so you've got
the visual system.

00:03:21.070 --> 00:03:22.860
And what we have
is the usual rule

00:03:22.860 --> 00:03:25.110
that visual information--
just like auditory,

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:27.870
just like tactile--
comes in, and goes

00:03:27.870 --> 00:03:30.760
by way of a way station along
the way, whose name we won't

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:33.540
worry about, and goes
through all these levels

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:36.520
of cortical processing,
and [? bio cort ?] people

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:39.460
will remember layer one,
doing dots, to lines,

00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:42.590
to moving lines, all of
that, eventually processing

00:03:42.590 --> 00:03:45.200
assessment, come up with
an idea that, oh, dear,

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.760
this is a menacing face.

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:49.110
And then let the
amygdala know about this.

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.400
What was also found
a number of years ago

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:53.330
is that there is a shortcut.

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:56.890
There is a branch coming off
of this way station called

00:03:56.890 --> 00:03:58.320
the lateral geniculate.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.370
There's a branch coming
off, which then is only one

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:03.445
synapse away from the amygdala.

00:04:03.445 --> 00:04:06.970
What we heard is
that's really useful,

00:04:06.970 --> 00:04:10.640
in that it can get you
fear-evoking, arousing

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:13.640
information that much faster
than going through all

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:15.040
this cortical processing.

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:16.399
It is a short cut.

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:18.500
It is not a one synapse away.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.940
But it certainly makes
for fewer synapses.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.030
That's a faster
system that we've

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.650
got in order to
very quickly pick up

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.120
information that
should be of interest

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:31.350
to the amygdala and all
of its fear, anxiety,

00:04:31.350 --> 00:04:32.977
aggression-type concerns.

00:04:32.977 --> 00:04:33.810
So that's wonderful.

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:35.380
That's terrific
for the amygdala.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:36.860
What I think we
also heard it is it

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:41.210
comes with a downside, which is
you send all this information

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:42.630
through all these
different steps

00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:45.450
there because it's doing
all this cortical processing

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:46.160
for you.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.170
It's figuring out
all the details

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:50.620
of the sensory information
you're getting in.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:53.520
This way, it gets to
the amygdala faster.

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:56.490
But what gets there
is less accurate.

00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:58.940
You're more likely
to make a mistake.

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:02.510
And that's the whole world of
people reacting really quickly

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:04.740
to some peripheral
piece of information,

00:05:04.740 --> 00:05:07.760
which turns out to be different
than they thought it was.

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.050
And before they knew
it, they had reacted.

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:13.080
This is the cortex sitting
there, still trying to decide,

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:14.770
is this a
three-dimensional object

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:16.110
or a two-dimensional one?

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:18.920
And through this route, you've
already stabbed the individual.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:23.990
This is a very, very clear
trade-off-- faster information,

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:25.070
less accurate.

00:05:25.070 --> 00:05:27.200
And there is, by now,
a lot of evidence

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:29.920
to suggest that this
particular pathway is

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.710
hyper excitable in individuals
with post-traumatic stress

00:05:33.710 --> 00:05:37.450
disorder, where that
whole world of all sorts

00:05:37.450 --> 00:05:42.070
of acute sensory stimuli
suddenly fling the person back

00:05:42.070 --> 00:05:45.200
into where they were when
that happened to them,

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:47.540
and without the processing
time to figure out,

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:49.510
this isn't exactly the same.

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:52.530
In fact, this is a world away
from where that happened.

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:55.200
Already, the amygdala
is responding.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.089
So these short cuts--
but telling you,

00:05:57.089 --> 00:05:59.130
one of the things you give
up with the short cuts

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:02.310
is the analytical accuracy.

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:05.630
OK, so amygdala for that,
amygdala equals fear,

00:06:05.630 --> 00:06:07.860
equals anxiety,
equals aggression.

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:09.170
Isn't that interesting?

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:11.660
In a world in which
amygdala is not afraid,

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:14.090
there's no aggression,
that whole theme there.

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:16.710
The amygdala isn't
always about fear,

00:06:16.710 --> 00:06:18.480
and aggression, and anxiety.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:20.610
And it's very
informative, the examples

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:22.420
where that's not the case.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:25.580
One case, really
interesting syndrome

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:27.357
called Williams
syndrome, which we're

00:06:27.357 --> 00:06:29.440
going to hear a lot about
in the language lecture.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:34.300
Williams syndrome appears to be
a poorly understood imprinted

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:37.620
genetic disorder where you
get, among other things,

00:06:37.620 --> 00:06:41.950
kids who are unbelievably
facile with language

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.030
and emotional expressivity.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:46.030
This whole world
of Williams kids,

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:48.060
it's this fascinating
disorder where

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:52.110
you get kids who are basically
borderline retarded in terms

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:53.370
of cognitive function.

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:57.140
Yet, they have this spectacular
adeptness at language,

00:06:57.140 --> 00:07:00.640
at reading emotions in other
people, at communicating them.

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:03.420
They are famously
affectionate kids

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:06.220
amid being very
cognitively impaired.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:07.680
We'll see in the
language lecture,

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:10.030
most people think
about Williams syndrome

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:13.820
as an interesting example of
the modularity of language

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:15.320
control in the cortex.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:20.050
You can have very, very
facile language skills

00:07:20.050 --> 00:07:22.760
in these individuals who,
nonetheless, are typically

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:25.990
in the IQ range of about
70, argument being,

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:28.720
we'll see in a couple of weeks,
that there are specialized

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.700
cortical areas for language.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:32.500
For our purposes,
the interesting thing

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:35.210
about Williams kids, and
eventually Williams adults,

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:38.540
is they are extremely trustful.

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:40.850
They are extremely gregarious.

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:44.220
They are incredibly
vulnerable as adults

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:47.200
to being taken advantage
of by other people.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:50.450
And what you see with Williams
individuals is you basically

00:07:50.450 --> 00:07:55.370
cannot evoke amygdala
activation with scary faces.

00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:58.100
They don't register in
someone with Williams.

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:01.090
So there, we see that
this is not universally

00:08:01.090 --> 00:08:02.760
serving that role.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:04.330
Another example
where there seems

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:06.210
to be an exception
until you think about it

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:09.190
a little bit, people
with social phobias.

00:08:09.190 --> 00:08:12.700
What studies have shown
is, show a social phobic

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:17.280
any sort of face-- human face--
and their amygdala activates.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:19.990
Oh, that's not telling
us anything informative.

00:08:19.990 --> 00:08:22.330
It's telling us something
very informative,

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:25.200
which is if you have a
severe social phobia,

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.820
any face is a scary face to you.

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:30.960
All faces do that, rather
than only ones communicating

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:33.490
certain threatening emotions.

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:35.530
Another one that seems
puzzling, but which

00:08:35.530 --> 00:08:38.080
then makes perfect sense
when you think about it, when

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:41.159
you take people with clinical
depression the amygdala

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:43.450
doesn't necessarily
activate when

00:08:43.450 --> 00:08:46.540
you show them a picture
of something frightening.

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:50.700
It activates when you show them
a picture of something sad.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:54.990
OK, so now instead of
doing fear and depression,

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:57.440
the amygdala does
sadness or something.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:08:58.920
If you think about
it for a minute,

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:00.600
that makes perfect sense.

00:09:00.600 --> 00:09:03.430
What the amygdala might
very well be doing

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:07.020
is responding to whatever it
is that is most ethologically

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:11.380
frightening to you-- you as a
species, you as an individual.

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:13.310
If you are somebody
who's depressed,

00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:15.020
the most frightening
thing on Earth

00:09:15.020 --> 00:09:18.690
is something sad around you, as
more justification for feeling

00:09:18.690 --> 00:09:21.730
even more depressed, the
amygdala being far more

00:09:21.730 --> 00:09:25.320
subtle than, oh, here's a scary
predator with a knife coming

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:28.850
at me, very much contextual.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:32.780
OK, another thing that the
amygdala is brilliant at,

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:35.220
which we will come
back to in more detail,

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:37.710
but on a first pass
it is so depressing,

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:40.930
is the amygdala is probably
the part of your brain

00:09:40.930 --> 00:09:44.827
that is best at doing
dichotomizing between us

00:09:44.827 --> 00:09:48.880
and them-- forming categories
in-group, out-group,

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:52.340
and responding to
out-group stimuli.

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:55.840
And we will see two things down
the line, probably on Friday.

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:59.670
Number one, it is
really, really depressing

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:01.730
how readily the
amygdala forms some

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:04.735
of these us-them dichotomies,
and the sort of them

00:10:04.735 --> 00:10:07.790
that it responds to--
really depressing.

00:10:07.790 --> 00:10:09.310
But also some good
news in there,

00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:12.990
remarkably subtle social
manipulations that

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:15.610
will change the sort
of us-them dichotomies

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:17.540
that the amygdala responds to.

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:19.440
So stay tuned for that.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:21.490
OK, so shifting
from the amygdala,

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:24.910
going to the incredibly
interesting and important

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:26.180
frontal cortex.

00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:28.710
And frontal cortex, obviously,
was doing all sorts of stuff

00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:31.120
two lectures ago
in the sex lecture,

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.530
getting you to have
the appropriate context

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:36.570
for sexual behavior, getting
to do the harder thing,

00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:39.200
like leaping over
streams, and head butting

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:41.300
with other antlered
beasts if that's

00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:42.590
part of your mating season.

00:10:42.590 --> 00:10:45.800
Where the frontal cortex
is particularly involved

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:49.770
is this whole world of
regulating appropriate behavior

00:10:49.770 --> 00:10:53.940
in the context of violence,
aggression, competition,

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:54.950
cooperation.

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:58.610
Frontal cortex is
incredibly important here.

00:10:58.610 --> 00:11:01.830
OK, back to the limbic
lecture-- the limbic system

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:06.450
is about sub-cortical structures
underneath, things like that.

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:08.570
And the cortex is
about the cortex.

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:10.150
And we heard in
the limbic lecture,

00:11:10.150 --> 00:11:12.740
instead what was originally
that heretical view

00:11:12.740 --> 00:11:15.120
by that neuroanatomist
Nauta saying,

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:18.250
actually, the frontal cortex
is part of the limbic system.

00:11:18.250 --> 00:11:19.520
It should be viewed as such.

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:21.650
And over the years since,
it being viewed as,

00:11:21.650 --> 00:11:24.760
this is the cortical part
of the limbic system.

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:28.710
This is the cortical region
that is intensely involved

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:31.290
with limbic function,
with emotional function.

00:11:31.290 --> 00:11:33.980
On an anatomical level,
what we've already seen

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:38.510
is just as a first pass, tons
of bidirectional connections,

00:11:38.510 --> 00:11:40.500
everything in the
limbic system talking

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:42.800
to the frontal
cortex, frontal cortex

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:45.550
sending projections back
over the limbic system.

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:47.930
So anatomically, it's there.

00:11:47.930 --> 00:11:51.430
So in terms of what it's doing--
the best way to describe what

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:53.910
the frontal cortex is
about is when there's

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:57.590
a choice between doing something
harder and something easier,

00:11:57.590 --> 00:11:59.830
and the harder thing is
the better thing to do,

00:11:59.830 --> 00:12:02.640
it's the thing that makes
you do the harder thing.

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:04.950
And we'll see this
plays out in all sorts

00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:07.520
of domains, the
frontal cortex getting

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:09.740
you to do the harder thing.

00:12:09.740 --> 00:12:14.330
First beginning to see the way
it works in terms of wiring--

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:16.970
OK, here we have
reduced the entire world

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:19.690
down to a simplified,
there's two neurons

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:22.149
that account for all the easier
things you do in your life.

00:12:22.149 --> 00:12:23.731
And there's three
neurons that account

00:12:23.731 --> 00:12:24.840
for all the harder ones.

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:27.400
Here, we have some
circumstance where

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:31.130
there's a circuit at some
juncture, the easier but less

00:12:31.130 --> 00:12:32.720
desirable outcome.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.840
Behavior is this way,
the harder one that way.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:40.950
And what you see is this has
more inputs then this one.

00:12:40.950 --> 00:12:44.280
This is obviously some
entire circuit of neurons.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:46.680
And this is highly
simplified, blah, blah.

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:48.630
But what we see is the
way it's set up here

00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:52.410
is that there are more
inputs into this pathway.

00:12:52.410 --> 00:12:54.990
This is what makes
this neuron easier

00:12:54.990 --> 00:12:57.050
to activate than this one.

00:12:57.050 --> 00:13:00.000
There are stronger
inputs into this pathway.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.800
This one has only two
axons going to it.

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:05.060
This one has three--
yes, simplified.

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:08.430
When you look at the wiring
of the frontal cortex,

00:13:08.430 --> 00:13:11.540
it's sending projections
all over the limbic system,

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:13.380
all over motor areas.

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:15.460
A characteristic
of the projections

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:19.880
is that very rarely are
they very strong projections

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:22.100
to any given target area.

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:25.700
They're not the sort of
projections where, here's

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:27.990
this frontal cortical
neuron that is now

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:31.300
dumping all of its axon
terminals into this one neuron

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:32.110
down there.

00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:35.210
It does not exert a
very strong influence

00:13:35.210 --> 00:13:38.430
over the excitation
of any given neuron.

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:42.830
Instead, what it has is a
whole lot of weak but diffuse

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:43.880
projections.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:46.370
What is the frontal
cortex doing?

00:13:46.370 --> 00:13:49.540
It's slowly massaging
the area there.

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:54.540
It is giving biasing bits of
de-polarization of excitation.

00:13:54.540 --> 00:13:58.004
So what we've got here
is-- OK, the numbers

00:13:58.004 --> 00:13:58.920
are not quite working.

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.940
But in any case,
what we have here is,

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:03.740
here's doing the right
thing that's harder.

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:05.850
And it's a lot harder
to get this neuron

00:14:05.850 --> 00:14:07.900
to do the right
thing that's harder,

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:10.360
because there is less of
an input than this pathway.

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:12.400
What the frontal
cortex tends to do

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:16.610
is have these relatively weak
inputs into all these systems

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:20.160
where it makes it a little
bit harder to just fall

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:21.130
for this one.

00:14:21.130 --> 00:14:23.840
It gives more strength
into this pathway.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:25.970
The frontal
projections very rarely

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:27.940
are activating on their own.

00:14:27.940 --> 00:14:32.260
Yes, indeed, we have another
example here of modulating.

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:35.080
If and only if this
pathway is already

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:37.020
struggling to do
the right thing,

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:40.030
the frontal cortex tends
to be able to push it

00:14:40.030 --> 00:14:42.060
over the top there
to pull it off.

00:14:42.060 --> 00:14:46.450
Frontal projections as very
diffuse, relatively weak,

00:14:46.450 --> 00:14:51.250
but biasing towards excitation,
rather than causing it,

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:54.660
that tends to be the
thing that it does.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:58.140
What you see in terms of making
sense of frontal function

00:14:58.140 --> 00:14:59.930
is, as we heard
the other day also,

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:04.270
a huge whopping projection
from that nucleus accumbens.

00:15:04.270 --> 00:15:06.830
You remember ventral
tegmental, nucleus accumbens,

00:15:06.830 --> 00:15:12.250
this huge dopamine releasing
projection into there.

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:15.390
And on a certain level--
you want a totally useless

00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:19.070
metaphor, but on a certain level
with the dopamine projection

00:15:19.070 --> 00:15:22.140
is about is-- so here, you've
got the frontal cortex.

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:23.740
The frontal cortex,
for a living,

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:25.510
makes you do the
harder thing when

00:15:25.510 --> 00:15:27.020
it's the right thing to do.

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:30.920
Dopamine is, in a sense,
the fuel for that activity.

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:35.320
Dopamine, the expectation,
the anticipation, the capacity

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:38.970
of dopamine to generate
goal-directed behaviors

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:41.460
is heavily running
through this pathway.

00:15:41.460 --> 00:15:43.530
Dopamine is a thing
that's giving,

00:15:43.530 --> 00:15:45.940
in a sense, the frontal
cortex the energy

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:48.870
to just push you over the
edge, and to tell you,

00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:52.790
yes, go this way instead of
this way, which also intrinsic

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:58.270
in this lots and lots of frontal
projections that are inhibitory

00:15:58.270 --> 00:15:59.180
in that realm.

00:15:59.180 --> 00:16:02.180
An awful lot of what
frontal cortex is also doing

00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:04.380
is whispering to
this pathway saying,

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:05.800
you really shouldn't do that.

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:07.120
You're going to regret it.

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:08.600
I know it's tempting right now.

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:12.470
Don't do it, don't do it-- this
super ego sort of neuroanatomy

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:16.780
there of frontal cortex,
dopamine as very strongly

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:20.250
stimulatory in there, the
whole role of dopamine

00:16:20.250 --> 00:16:23.140
as driving
goal-directed behavior.

00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:25.540
And that was that critical
business we saw in that study

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:28.680
showing you let the monkey
know that it's now entered one

00:16:28.680 --> 00:16:30.930
of those periods where
if it lever presses,

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:32.072
it gets the reward.

00:16:32.072 --> 00:16:35.350
Oh, I know just how this works--
anticipation, that's great.

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:36.600
Up goes dopamine.

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:39.080
If you prevent the
dopamine from going up,

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:41.070
you don't get the
lever pressing.

00:16:41.070 --> 00:16:44.090
Dopamine is not just
about anticipation.

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:48.370
Dopamine is about driving
the behavior needed

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:50.650
to get the reward that
you are anticipating,

00:16:50.650 --> 00:16:54.250
dopamine as
goal-directed behavior.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:57.200
OK, so what you
begin to see in terms

00:16:57.200 --> 00:17:00.350
of how this frontal
cortex does this making

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:03.570
you do the harder thing,
it's manifest in all sorts

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:04.609
of domains.

00:17:04.609 --> 00:17:06.470
Easiest, most
accessible realm is

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:08.770
seeing what it has
to do with cognition,

00:17:08.770 --> 00:17:10.819
the way in which the
frontal cortex gets

00:17:10.819 --> 00:17:12.339
you to do the harder thing.

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:16.480
What it helps you to do is
organize bits of information

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:19.690
in ways that makes it
easier to make sense of.

00:17:19.690 --> 00:17:22.700
Here is, if you ever find
yourself being borderline

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:24.680
demented, and somebody
is giving you a test,

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:26.805
this is one of the tests
they're going to give you.

00:17:26.805 --> 00:17:27.760
So start preparing.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:30.190
This is this
horrifying test called

00:17:30.190 --> 00:17:34.650
the CVLT-- the California
Verbal Learning Task

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:36.110
or some such thing like that.

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:37.110
But here's what they do.

00:17:37.110 --> 00:17:39.000
Some neuropsychologist
sits you down.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.294
And says, oh, I'm just
going to tell you something,

00:17:41.294 --> 00:17:42.210
a list of things here.

00:17:42.210 --> 00:17:43.440
See if you can remember.

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:45.140
Today I went to the market.

00:17:45.140 --> 00:17:50.220
And I bought one tomato, one
hammer, one box of cereal,

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:53.310
one grape, one-- and
goes through a list of 16

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:55.330
of these, one
every second or so.

00:17:55.330 --> 00:17:56.000
And they finish.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:56.615
And they say.

00:17:56.615 --> 00:17:58.990
OK, do you happen to remember
what I bought at the market

00:17:58.990 --> 00:17:59.640
today?

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:01.860
Oh my God, it is so stressful.

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:04.760
So you manage to get out like
maybe seven of them correct.

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:07.127
And the person says,
OK, that's very good.

00:18:07.127 --> 00:18:07.960
Let's do that again.

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:09.170
Today, I went to the market.

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:13.080
And I brought one tomato, one
hammer, one box of Cheerios,

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:15.320
one box of-- and goes
through this list again,

00:18:15.320 --> 00:18:17.870
and seeing each time how
many of them you remember,

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:20.500
beginning to see your
memory acquisition

00:18:20.500 --> 00:18:22.885
thing as you're getting closer
and closer to remembering

00:18:22.885 --> 00:18:24.370
all 16.

00:18:24.370 --> 00:18:27.410
It's not until you're maybe
in the third or fourth round

00:18:27.410 --> 00:18:29.470
of doing this that
you begin to notice

00:18:29.470 --> 00:18:34.650
something, which is of the 16
items four of them are fruits.

00:18:34.650 --> 00:18:37.130
Four of them are hardware items.

00:18:37.130 --> 00:18:39.840
Four of them are
bread cereal things.

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:41.206
Four of them are who knows what.

00:18:41.206 --> 00:18:42.580
And they're
scattered throughout.

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:44.500
What the people
typically start doing

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:47.540
by the third or fourth
one is you begin to group

00:18:47.540 --> 00:18:48.970
them by categories.

00:18:48.970 --> 00:18:54.520
And instead of remembering back
OK, tomato, hammer, cereal,

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:58.100
fruit, whatever, you first
tell the three out of the four

00:18:58.100 --> 00:18:59.600
fruits that you remember.

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:01.980
Then you tell the two out
of the four hardware items.

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:05.030
You are beginning to
group the information.

00:19:05.030 --> 00:19:08.170
And what that is called
is executive function.

00:19:08.170 --> 00:19:11.000
Executive organizing
strategy, it

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:16.240
is sheer memory systems that are
remembering these 16 factoids.

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:19.080
It is executive organizing
that's telling you,

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:20.790
do you notice some
patterns there?

00:19:20.790 --> 00:19:22.640
Don't just remember
it in sequence.

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:24.900
Don't try to just
remember it in sequence.

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:26.070
Stop for a second.

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:27.972
And try to keep track
of the categories,

00:19:27.972 --> 00:19:29.430
because that's
going to be a better

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:31.060
strategy in the long run.

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:33.200
That's what the
frontal cortex does.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:35.720
You get someone with
frontal cortical damage,

00:19:35.720 --> 00:19:38.710
and their capacity to
remember, the learning curve

00:19:38.710 --> 00:19:41.030
is not all that different
from anyone else.

00:19:41.030 --> 00:19:43.380
But they never start
doing the grouping.

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:46.750
They never start doing what
we might think of as almost

00:19:46.750 --> 00:19:49.290
cognitive strategizing.

00:19:49.290 --> 00:19:50.990
Oh, I see a pattern here.

00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:54.030
And I suspect if I put
the effort into exploiting

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:56.990
that pattern, it's going to
make it more productive for me

00:19:56.990 --> 00:19:59.460
to try to remember things
rather than just trying

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:00.680
to do it in sequence.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:03.290
So the frontal cortex
is good for that.

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:05.610
Where else do you get
in the cognitive realm

00:20:05.610 --> 00:20:09.080
the frontal cortex getting
you to do the harder thing?

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:10.930
Where you get all
this information

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:13.290
in the cognitive realm
is when you study people

00:20:13.290 --> 00:20:16.510
with frontal damage-- either
people with accidents,

00:20:16.510 --> 00:20:20.310
or very often older individuals
who have strokes there.

00:20:20.310 --> 00:20:22.430
There's a very distinctive
type of dementia

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:25.140
that takes out the
frontal cortex called

00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:26.310
frontotemporal dementia.

00:20:26.310 --> 00:20:28.610
And all sorts of cognitive
tests in those cases

00:20:28.610 --> 00:20:31.140
showing in the
cognitive realm what

00:20:31.140 --> 00:20:34.310
happens when you're not
having this going on

00:20:34.310 --> 00:20:36.120
throughout all the circuitry.

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:37.580
One thing that
would be given-- OK,

00:20:37.580 --> 00:20:39.390
so you sit down this individual.

00:20:39.390 --> 00:20:43.540
And you say, OK, you
recognize this, don't you?

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:45.730
Even though most of you
guys don't by now growing up

00:20:45.730 --> 00:20:47.040
in the digital era.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:48.792
But this is the face of a clock.

00:20:48.792 --> 00:20:50.750
And it comes with a little
hand and a big hand.

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:52.730
And they point in
informative directions.

00:20:52.730 --> 00:20:55.760
So you ask the person,
OK, you recognize this.

00:20:55.760 --> 00:20:57.260
Of course, this is a clock face.

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:59.280
Now, where would
you draw the hands

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:03.490
if I said the time was 11:10?

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:05.770
11:10, so sit for a minute,
and think about where.

00:21:05.770 --> 00:21:08.212
And, of course, it's
10 minutes after 11:00.

00:21:08.212 --> 00:21:09.920
And that's that where
the hands would go.

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:14.170
Someone with frontal damage,
instead, would draw the hands

00:21:14.170 --> 00:21:16.170
at 11 and 10.

00:21:16.170 --> 00:21:17.520
What are the rest of us doing?

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:18.960
We're saying, OK,
the easier thing

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:22.210
is to just get gummed
up on the number 11

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:24.670
and the number 10-- wait,
wait, don't do that.

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:28.020
Hold on, remember,
10 is a coding

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:30.240
for multiples of five
minutes, because that's

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:31.770
the way clocks are organized.

00:21:31.770 --> 00:21:33.600
So 10 is actually two of these.

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:35.100
So it's 11:10.

00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:37.780
10 is a shorthand for
saying 10 minutes after.

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:39.530
And you put your hands
in the right place.

00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:42.240
Somebody with frontal
damage can't hold off.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:45.340
And they get pulled by
the easiest interpretation

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:47.150
of the sound 11:10.

00:21:47.150 --> 00:21:49.790
They draw the
hands at 11 and 10.

00:21:49.790 --> 00:21:51.770
So this is what you would see.

00:21:51.770 --> 00:21:55.000
More examples-- what the
frontal cortex is good at

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.910
is getting you to
inhibit the easier

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:00.400
route when it is a
very well-learned, very

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:01.750
well-conditioned one.

00:22:01.750 --> 00:22:02.810
Here's what you would do.

00:22:02.810 --> 00:22:04.351
Now you take the
person who you think

00:22:04.351 --> 00:22:05.630
may have some frontal damage.

00:22:05.630 --> 00:22:08.250
And you say, OK, here's
a task I want you to do.

00:22:08.250 --> 00:22:11.140
Starting with December,
tell me the months

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:13.110
of the year backwards.

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:16.010
What have we all learned
since way back in first grade

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:16.900
or whatever?

00:22:16.900 --> 00:22:19.720
That this is an easy
thing going forward.

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:21.650
This is the harder
thing right now.

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:23.590
And you will see a person
with frontal damage

00:22:23.590 --> 00:22:31.990
will say OK, December, November,
October, September, October,

00:22:31.990 --> 00:22:33.100
November, December.

00:22:33.100 --> 00:22:35.260
They manage to pull
it off for a while.

00:22:35.260 --> 00:22:38.890
And then they just slip on the
ice back into the easier way.

00:22:38.890 --> 00:22:41.530
It is, you normally
have December followed

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:43.930
by January, not by November.

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:46.060
It takes more work
to do it that way.

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:49.340
People with frontal damage,
they have this intrusion.

00:22:49.340 --> 00:22:53.150
They can't hold off the
over-learned response,

00:22:53.150 --> 00:22:55.720
the more habitual response.

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:57.950
You would then see with
frontal damage something

00:22:57.950 --> 00:22:59.539
that's termed intrusions.

00:22:59.539 --> 00:23:01.830
Now you would say to the same
person, OK, that's great.

00:23:01.830 --> 00:23:02.371
That's great.

00:23:02.371 --> 00:23:05.090
Now what I want you to do
is start with the number 20

00:23:05.090 --> 00:23:06.560
and count backwards.

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:14.810
And the person will say, OK, 20,
19, 18, 17, September, October,

00:23:14.810 --> 00:23:15.990
November, December.

00:23:15.990 --> 00:23:18.830
And they've slipped back
into the previous task.

00:23:18.830 --> 00:23:21.102
They don't have the
effort here to say,

00:23:21.102 --> 00:23:22.810
we've stopped it with
the months already.

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:23.950
Now we're doing numbers.

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:26.420
Don't slip back into
that month stuff.

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:28.860
But, yet, that's
exactly what occurs.

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:30.800
You take somebody
with frontal damage.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:33.550
You give them would be
called a verbal fluency test.

00:23:33.550 --> 00:23:36.460
You say, OK, one minute,
tell me as many words

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:39.637
as you could think of starting
with the letter F. Great.

00:23:39.637 --> 00:23:41.220
Now tell me as many
words as you could

00:23:41.220 --> 00:23:43.370
think of starting with the
letter M, with the letter P,

00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:43.960
so on.

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:47.350
And you go with the letter
M. And by the fifth word,

00:23:47.350 --> 00:23:50.810
they're back to words with
F. The previous task intrudes

00:23:50.810 --> 00:23:51.560
in there.

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:54.452
It has trouble
organizing, strategizing,

00:23:54.452 --> 00:23:55.910
we're done with
the letter F. We're

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:57.400
done with doing the months.

00:23:57.400 --> 00:23:59.320
Concentrate now,
we're doing the letter

00:23:59.320 --> 00:24:01.390
M. We're doing
numbers backwards.

00:24:01.390 --> 00:24:04.830
Don't fall for the easy
version of just saying 11:10.

00:24:04.830 --> 00:24:07.490
This is the stuff the
frontal cortex does.

00:24:07.490 --> 00:24:10.530
This is what it looks like
when you are getting damage

00:24:10.530 --> 00:24:12.710
to the frontal cortex.

00:24:12.710 --> 00:24:15.190
So cognitive aspects
of that-- what's

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:19.040
the frontal cortex particularly
good at in the cognitive realm?

00:24:19.040 --> 00:24:23.920
It is making you work, and work,
and work for a cognitive reward

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:25.160
way down the line.

00:24:25.160 --> 00:24:27.790
And that's the entire world
of all of you guys already

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:30.400
gunning for the perfect
GPA that will get you

00:24:30.400 --> 00:24:32.350
into a good nursing
home someday.

00:24:32.350 --> 00:24:36.060
That is your frontal cortex
working to your advantage.

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:38.930
That's your frontal cortex
doing that, this task

00:24:38.930 --> 00:24:41.400
of gratification postponement.

00:24:41.400 --> 00:24:43.010
Do the harder thing.

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:45.360
Where am I going to
get the energy for it?

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:47.930
It's these frontal
inputs that's just

00:24:47.930 --> 00:24:52.250
biasing so I could do the harder
pathway rather than the easier.

00:24:52.250 --> 00:24:55.230
You find this also when you're
doing electrophysiological,

00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:57.510
when you're recording, you're
sticking in electrodes,

00:24:57.510 --> 00:24:59.560
and seeing when
neurons are excited.

00:24:59.560 --> 00:25:01.710
Suppose, for example,
you've got a monkey.

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:03.100
And you are recording.

00:25:03.100 --> 00:25:05.500
You have electrodes both
in the visual cortex

00:25:05.500 --> 00:25:07.960
and some other ones
in the frontal cortex.

00:25:07.960 --> 00:25:10.490
And, again, this is one
of those tasks where

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:14.010
when the bell sounds--
bells don't beep,

00:25:14.010 --> 00:25:16.380
when some buzzer beeps, it
means to the monkey, now,

00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:18.327
OK, every time
the light goes on,

00:25:18.327 --> 00:25:19.910
you have to press a
lever three times.

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:21.260
And you get a reward.

00:25:21.260 --> 00:25:22.010
That's the rule.

00:25:22.010 --> 00:25:24.810
Buzzer means we're starting
one of those testing sessions

00:25:24.810 --> 00:25:25.430
again.

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:28.240
Light comes on, hit lever,
light comes on, hit lever.

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:31.364
So you record from
the visual cortex.

00:25:31.364 --> 00:25:32.530
And here's what's happening.

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.430
This is when the
buzzer comes on saying,

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:37.510
oh, we've just started
one of these test periods.

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:39.220
And now the light flashes.

00:25:39.220 --> 00:25:42.320
And the visual cortex
activates each time.

00:25:42.320 --> 00:25:44.860
What's going on in
the frontal cortex?

00:25:44.860 --> 00:25:48.840
The second the buzzer goes off,
the frontal cortex activates.

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:52.410
And it stays up the whole time.

00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:55.090
What is the visual
cortex coding for?

00:25:55.090 --> 00:25:58.060
Individual examples
of this task.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:00.210
What's the frontal
cortex coding for?

00:26:00.210 --> 00:26:02.453
It's remembering the rule.

00:26:02.453 --> 00:26:04.770
OK, the buzzer went on.

00:26:04.770 --> 00:26:06.760
That means-- now,
remember, remember,

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:09.780
remember for the next whatever
period of time, get ready.

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:12.590
Every time the light
flashes, hit the lever there.

00:26:12.590 --> 00:26:15.140
The task of the
frontal cortex is

00:26:15.140 --> 00:26:18.380
to maintain the rule
throughout, transcending

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:20.650
the individual examples of it.

00:26:20.650 --> 00:26:22.580
So you can already
see where we're

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:25.350
heading with moral
development in kids,

00:26:25.350 --> 00:26:27.134
and frontal maturation.

00:26:27.134 --> 00:26:28.800
And all of that's
going to fit in really

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:31.600
well, the frontal cortex
doing stuff like that.

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:35.230
What you should begin to notice
is intrinsic in all of this,

00:26:35.230 --> 00:26:37.740
the frontal cortex is
sending these projections

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:39.110
all over the brain.

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:42.530
The frontal cortex does not
code for individual examples

00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:46.410
of rules, but instead maintains
rules for long, long periods.

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:49.860
The frontal cortex
works really hard.

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:53.190
Frontal cortical neurons have
very high metabolic rates.

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:56.990
And a whole world of neurology,
thus, is built around the fact

00:26:56.990 --> 00:26:59.830
that frontal cortical
neurons are very fragile.

00:26:59.830 --> 00:27:01.540
They die very readily.

00:27:01.540 --> 00:27:04.040
All sorts of
neurological disorders

00:27:04.040 --> 00:27:07.400
damage the frontal cortex
with behavioral changes

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:09.730
that go along with that.

00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:12.730
So you've got the wiring,
the patterning, all of that.

00:27:12.730 --> 00:27:15.980
But then at some point
you wonder, well, I

00:27:15.980 --> 00:27:17.310
learn all sorts of rules.

00:27:17.310 --> 00:27:19.430
Back when I was about
three years old,

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:22.870
I learned this rule having
to do with no more diapers.

00:27:22.870 --> 00:27:24.750
And if you go to the
potty, you get M&amp;Ms.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:27.640
And, in fact, I sort of
have internalized this.

00:27:27.640 --> 00:27:30.840
And same does that mean the,
you need to go to the bathroom

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:34.340
now is internalized that there's
a frontal cortical neuron that

00:27:34.340 --> 00:27:36.100
got excited when I
was three years old

00:27:36.100 --> 00:27:39.460
and got toilet trained, and has
been firing ever since then?

00:27:39.460 --> 00:27:44.120
No, what you see after a while
is the frontal cortical realm

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:45.274
of remember.

00:27:45.274 --> 00:27:47.690
Remember, you go to the bathroom
when you need to do this.

00:27:47.690 --> 00:27:49.648
Remember, remember, you
say the months forward.

00:27:49.648 --> 00:27:51.280
Remember all these
sorts of things.

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:54.200
At some point, it
becomes automatic.

00:27:54.200 --> 00:27:56.350
It becomes reflexive.

00:27:56.350 --> 00:27:58.750
And what is seen
is at that point,

00:27:58.750 --> 00:28:03.020
the frontal cortex stops
being the area that is active.

00:28:03.020 --> 00:28:05.030
At some point,
instead, it becomes

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:08.630
implicit procedural pathways.

00:28:08.630 --> 00:28:11.290
It gets stored
elsewhere in the brain.

00:28:11.290 --> 00:28:14.990
What you see in individuals
with Alzheimer's disease

00:28:14.990 --> 00:28:17.860
where you get a lot of
damage to the hippocampus

00:28:17.860 --> 00:28:20.440
and the cortex-- particularly
the frontal cortex-- what

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:24.220
you see is all sorts of things
that were learned way back

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:27.470
when, and learned enough
to just be habitual,

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:29.200
people can still do.

00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:33.210
You will have somebody who
is demented enough that they

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:36.660
cannot tell you what decade it
is, the name of their spouse,

00:28:36.660 --> 00:28:39.120
the name of their children,
how many children they have,

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:39.750
whatever.

00:28:39.750 --> 00:28:43.110
But this is someone who
still knows how to knit.

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:45.780
They learned when they were
seven years old how to knit.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:48.490
And now 80 years later,
they can still do that.

00:28:48.490 --> 00:28:51.810
This is not the frontal cortex
remembering the knitting rules

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:54.260
for the last 70 years or so.

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:58.190
This is, it became automatic
and got moved elsewhere.

00:28:58.190 --> 00:29:00.590
And a whole bizarre
world you see

00:29:00.590 --> 00:29:02.717
with frontal damage
in individuals

00:29:02.717 --> 00:29:04.800
with these dementias where
some of the things that

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:09.290
become automatic are remarkable,
suggesting that you've

00:29:09.290 --> 00:29:12.160
got storage capacity in
other places in the brain

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:14.050
when you don't
have to consciously

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:17.390
think about it, when something
has become so automatic.

00:29:17.390 --> 00:29:21.110
You go to the bathroom when
you need to void your bladder.

00:29:21.110 --> 00:29:23.250
OK, we don't have to
think about that anymore.

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:26.320
It has now gotten to
a pathway like this.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:29.490
Other brain regions
particularly, the cerebellum,

00:29:29.490 --> 00:29:31.580
seems to play a
larger role in that.

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:32.570
Stay tuned.

00:29:32.570 --> 00:29:35.800
We are going to be getting
to a very interesting point

00:29:35.800 --> 00:29:37.940
about moral development in kids.

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:40.950
When do certain moral
rules stop having

00:29:40.950 --> 00:29:43.280
to be coded in the
frontal cortex,

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:46.340
and instead become as
habitual as toilet training?

00:29:46.340 --> 00:29:48.550
We'll see some really
interesting implications

00:29:48.550 --> 00:29:49.810
of that.

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:53.500
OK, so what do you see when
you get frontal damage?

00:29:53.500 --> 00:29:56.830
You get all these
cognitive problems there,

00:29:56.830 --> 00:29:59.790
and these problems with doing
the harder but more correct

00:29:59.790 --> 00:30:01.040
thing cognitively.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:03.460
You see it as well
in terms of doing

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:05.900
the harder but more
correct thing in terms

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:08.180
of behavior, social behavior.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:10.790
First classic
example of this, they

00:30:10.790 --> 00:30:12.677
take away your
neurobiology license

00:30:12.677 --> 00:30:14.510
if you don't mention
this guy at some point.

00:30:14.510 --> 00:30:17.640
How many of you have
heard to Phineas Gage?

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:20.060
How many of you have not
heard of Phineas Gage?

00:30:20.060 --> 00:30:21.645
OK, time for Phineas Gage.

00:30:21.645 --> 00:30:23.520
OK, but the ones who
have heard of him, let's

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:24.890
all say this in unison.

00:30:24.890 --> 00:30:28.230
OK, Phineas Gage was the
first identified individual

00:30:28.230 --> 00:30:30.150
to have massive frontal damage.

00:30:30.150 --> 00:30:33.870
Phineas Gage was a foreman
on a railroad construction

00:30:33.870 --> 00:30:36.050
line in Vermont in the 1840s.

00:30:36.050 --> 00:30:39.440
One day, thanks to somebody or
other doing something wrong,

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:41.820
there was an explosion
of some dynamite, which

00:30:41.820 --> 00:30:44.610
blew a large metal rod
through his forehead

00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:48.020
and out the other side,
taking out his frontal cortex

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:49.420
in the process.

00:30:49.420 --> 00:30:50.940
And this was rather dramatic.

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:52.450
And this was this
large metal pole

00:30:52.450 --> 00:30:55.400
that went through fast enough
that, in fact, cauterized

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:56.550
all the blood vessels.

00:30:56.550 --> 00:30:59.710
And you can see that metal pole
at the museum in the Harvard

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:01.650
Med School Library,
where you can also

00:31:01.650 --> 00:31:04.120
see his skull, which
is very interesting,

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:06.970
because the rest of Phineas
Gage is about 20 miles from here

00:31:06.970 --> 00:31:07.920
buried in Colma.

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:10.126
So I don't quite know
how his skull wound up

00:31:10.126 --> 00:31:11.250
at that end of the country.

00:31:11.250 --> 00:31:13.630
But in the either case, he
was buried in San Francisco,

00:31:13.630 --> 00:31:17.140
minus-- well, I guess the Dean
of Harvard Med School swooped

00:31:17.140 --> 00:31:17.640
in.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:19.700
And before you knew it,
the skull was on its way

00:31:19.700 --> 00:31:20.950
east there with the metal rod.

00:31:20.950 --> 00:31:23.770
But in any case,
OK, so Phineas Gage

00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:27.180
had his frontal cortex
splattered 15 feet behind him.

00:31:27.180 --> 00:31:29.720
And what happened
was, amazingly,

00:31:29.720 --> 00:31:32.000
because it went through
with such force and so fast,

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.240
that it cauterized
all the blood vessels,

00:31:34.240 --> 00:31:37.940
he was actually, like, able
to get up at that point.

00:31:37.940 --> 00:31:40.500
And, most remarkably, with
a bunch of people from work,

00:31:40.500 --> 00:31:42.930
he was able to walk
a mile and a half

00:31:42.930 --> 00:31:46.440
to the nearest doctor, who
being a good diagnostician,

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:48.730
took a look at Phineas Gage,
and tilted his head back.

00:31:48.730 --> 00:31:50.271
And looked, and he
said, whoa, you've

00:31:50.271 --> 00:31:52.259
got a hole there in
your head, and was

00:31:52.259 --> 00:31:54.050
sort of looking in more
detail, and saying,

00:31:54.050 --> 00:31:56.920
whoa, you've got frontal cortex
got blown out of your head

00:31:56.920 --> 00:31:57.420
there.

00:31:57.420 --> 00:32:01.330
And this was sort of the peak of
diagnostic skills at the time.

00:32:01.330 --> 00:32:04.986
But what happened was the boss
there on the railroad line

00:32:04.986 --> 00:32:07.860
said, Gage, you know what?

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:09.120
Take the rest of the day off.

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:10.210
See you tomorrow.

00:32:10.210 --> 00:32:11.330
So Gage goes home.

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:14.630
And the next day he returns, not
just figuratively but literally

00:32:14.630 --> 00:32:16.370
transformed overnight.

00:32:16.370 --> 00:32:19.210
Gage, who was this
sober, sobrietous,

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:22.940
religious man, highly reliable
foreman of this entire work

00:32:22.940 --> 00:32:23.930
place, et cetera.

00:32:23.930 --> 00:32:26.380
Gage was never able
to work a day steadily

00:32:26.380 --> 00:32:27.660
for the rest of his life.

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:32.420
He became this brawling,
abusive, sexually predatory,

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:33.880
out of control individual.

00:32:33.880 --> 00:32:37.080
And that original doctor,
seeing what he turned into,

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:38.580
was the first one
who said, well,

00:32:38.580 --> 00:32:41.390
whatever that part of the brain
was that got taken out there,

00:32:41.390 --> 00:32:43.950
whatever it was, that
part of the brain

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:46.990
reigns in our animal energies.

00:32:46.990 --> 00:32:51.380
And 170 years later, there's
not a hugely better definition

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:54.540
out there as to what the
frontal cortex is about.

00:32:54.540 --> 00:32:58.760
So Phineas Gage being
the official first one,

00:32:58.760 --> 00:33:00.280
and you learn all
about this guy.

00:33:00.280 --> 00:33:02.800
But very interestingly,
about a year ago somebody

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:06.000
found the very first
photograph of Phineas Gage.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:07.510
And go look at that online.

00:33:07.510 --> 00:33:11.250
What's interesting is he looks
like a perfectly normal guy.

00:33:11.250 --> 00:33:14.280
The pole took out his eye
along with the frontal cortex.

00:33:14.280 --> 00:33:16.840
And, obviously, there
was that problem.

00:33:16.840 --> 00:33:19.860
But this is, like, the face
of somebody from the 1850s.

00:33:19.860 --> 00:33:21.360
And there's something,
I don't know,

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:23.600
I found very moving
about seeing this face

00:33:23.600 --> 00:33:25.520
that everybody learns
about Phineas Gage.

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:28.540
And everybody has seen his
skull, and the reconstruction

00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:29.420
of the accident.

00:33:29.420 --> 00:33:30.630
And that's right.

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:32.830
This was, like, a
regular old person

00:33:32.830 --> 00:33:35.270
whose life was
completely destroyed

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:37.760
when the frontal
cortex scattered

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:40.850
all behind him there--
remarkable first example

00:33:40.850 --> 00:33:41.470
of that.

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:44.730
Since then, most of the evidence
for what frontal cortex is

00:33:44.730 --> 00:33:47.610
about from damage
is older individuals

00:33:47.610 --> 00:33:50.562
who have stroke damage
to the frontal cortex.

00:33:50.562 --> 00:33:52.770
And what I mentioned, I
think, in the limbic lecture,

00:33:52.770 --> 00:33:55.030
one example of what
this looks like was

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:58.570
a horrifying case in a
facility in the East Bay

00:33:58.570 --> 00:34:01.130
some years ago where
an 80-year-old man who

00:34:01.130 --> 00:34:03.760
had had extensive frontal
damage due to a stroke

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:06.320
was found to have raped
an 80-year-old woman

00:34:06.320 --> 00:34:07.880
with Alzheimer's disease.

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:11.699
This is what frontal damage
looks like in an 80-year-old.

00:34:11.699 --> 00:34:14.590
Here's something very
interesting to consider,

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:16.600
and seeing exactly
the terrain we're

00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:19.530
heading into here with
this sort of information,

00:34:19.530 --> 00:34:25.290
approximately 25% of men on
death row in this country

00:34:25.290 --> 00:34:27.570
have a history of
concussive head trauma

00:34:27.570 --> 00:34:29.600
to the front of their head.

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:32.110
Front of the head,
where you wind up

00:34:32.110 --> 00:34:35.790
damaging the front of the
brain, frontal cortical damage.

00:34:35.790 --> 00:34:39.130
And what we enter into
here is this whole realm

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:43.400
where this stuff is stupefyingly
relevant to making sense

00:34:43.400 --> 00:34:47.130
of criminal behavior in
humans-- possibilities

00:34:47.130 --> 00:34:48.760
of frontal damage.

00:34:48.760 --> 00:34:51.540
Currently, there
is one law that's

00:34:51.540 --> 00:34:54.190
on the books in the majority
of states in this country

00:34:54.190 --> 00:34:58.470
for deciding when somebody is so
organically impaired that they

00:34:58.470 --> 00:35:00.670
count as having an
insanity defense,

00:35:00.670 --> 00:35:05.300
rather than being criminally
culpable for their acts.

00:35:05.300 --> 00:35:07.800
And this is something
called the McNaughton rule.

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:09.930
McNaughton rule,
everybody gets taught.

00:35:09.930 --> 00:35:12.750
What the McNaughton rule
is, can the individual

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:16.020
tell the difference
between right and wrong?

00:35:16.020 --> 00:35:18.640
This is the gold
standard in courts

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:22.490
as to whether or not somebody
gets a organically impaired

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:24.560
insanity defense ruling or not.

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:28.850
McNaughton, whose work was
all of this cutting edge

00:35:28.850 --> 00:35:32.480
neurobiology was based on,
McNaughton was most probably

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:35.530
a paranoid schizophrenic,
a guy in 1840

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:38.370
who attempted to assassinate
the Prime Minister of England,

00:35:38.370 --> 00:35:42.170
and was so clearly,
clearly psychotic

00:35:42.170 --> 00:35:43.910
that this was the
first case of the jury

00:35:43.910 --> 00:35:46.640
formally saying that,
no, there is something

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:50.130
too sick about this man to hold
him responsible for his acts.

00:35:50.130 --> 00:35:52.520
And the clearest thing that
came through in that trial

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:55.700
was, he could not
distinguish right from wrong.

00:35:55.700 --> 00:35:57.600
And the sort of
thing that absolutely

00:35:57.600 --> 00:36:00.930
does in somebody attempting
to a McNaughton defense

00:36:00.930 --> 00:36:03.030
in a criminal trial
is if there's evidence

00:36:03.030 --> 00:36:06.170
that they tried to cover
their tracks afterward,

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:09.160
that they were aware that
they had done something

00:36:09.160 --> 00:36:10.570
which was unacceptable.

00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:12.357
What you see with
people who can't

00:36:12.357 --> 00:36:14.190
tell the difference
between right and wrong,

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:15.700
there is no evidence
of them trying

00:36:15.700 --> 00:36:16.920
to cover up their tracks.

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:20.020
Where do you see the McNaughton
rule standardly applied?

00:36:20.020 --> 00:36:22.590
Severe, severe schizophrenics.

00:36:22.590 --> 00:36:24.990
And, for example, John
Hinckley, the person

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:34.580
who tried to assassinate
Reagan in the 1980s,

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:37.620
and he was found
innocent-- or guilty

00:36:37.620 --> 00:36:40.000
with an insanity
defense, because he

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:43.250
failed a McNaughton ruling,
severe schizophrenic.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:46.350
So this has been the gold
standard in most of the courts,

00:36:46.350 --> 00:36:48.120
in most of the states,
in this country.

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:51.580
The only way you could
be held not accountable

00:36:51.580 --> 00:36:54.530
for your criminal actions
because of organic impairment

00:36:54.530 --> 00:36:56.450
would be if you can't
tell the difference

00:36:56.450 --> 00:36:59.350
between right and wrong.

00:36:59.350 --> 00:37:01.830
But then you've got a problem,
because you get people

00:37:01.830 --> 00:37:03.570
with frontal cortical damage.

00:37:03.570 --> 00:37:06.700
And they can tell the difference
between right and wrong.

00:37:06.700 --> 00:37:07.900
They know the rules.

00:37:07.900 --> 00:37:09.630
They can state them for you.

00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:12.460
Yet, they can't control
their behaviors.

00:37:12.460 --> 00:37:14.680
And this comes through
with all sorts of tests.

00:37:14.680 --> 00:37:18.120
But you could show this now
with people with frontal damage.

00:37:18.120 --> 00:37:21.310
And, for example, here's the
M&amp;M test that you give them.

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:23.720
And what you've got is
something desirable.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:26.280
In this hand, you have
five M&amp;Ms. In this hand,

00:37:26.280 --> 00:37:27.320
you have one.

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:30.770
And the rule is, if the person
reaches for the five M&amp;Ms,

00:37:30.770 --> 00:37:32.380
you pull your hand away quickly.

00:37:32.380 --> 00:37:34.690
And they get one
M&amp;M as a reward.

00:37:34.690 --> 00:37:37.670
If they reach for the one
M&amp;M, you pull your hand away.

00:37:37.670 --> 00:37:39.470
And you give them five M&amp;Ms.

00:37:39.470 --> 00:37:42.440
In other words, can they
be disciplined enough

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:45.100
to not reach for the
five M&amp;M, and instead

00:37:45.100 --> 00:37:46.750
hold out and go for one?

00:37:46.750 --> 00:37:48.800
You get more of a
reward that way.

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:51.930
By doing the harder thing,
you will get more of a reward.

00:37:51.930 --> 00:37:54.600
Extensive frontal
damage, they never,

00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:57.360
ever, ever are able to
reach for the one M&amp;M.

00:37:57.360 --> 00:38:01.160
They always get pulled
towards the easier solution--

00:38:01.160 --> 00:38:03.490
the easier, more
superficial way.

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:05.790
There's five M&amp;Ms.
That's what I want.

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:08.550
Instead of being able to
do the executive stepping

00:38:08.550 --> 00:38:12.630
back, and saying, if I go for a
one right now, I will get five.

00:38:12.630 --> 00:38:16.140
What is remarkable is you get an
individual with frontal damage.

00:38:16.140 --> 00:38:18.870
And they will tell
you what the rule is.

00:38:18.870 --> 00:38:21.270
They will sit there
and say, I know.

00:38:21.270 --> 00:38:22.510
I know what you're up to.

00:38:22.510 --> 00:38:24.000
You want me to grab the five.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:25.125
But then I'll only get one.

00:38:25.125 --> 00:38:28.420
What I need to do is grab the--
and then they go for the five.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:31.040
They can verbalize
the rule right there.

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:34.170
They know the difference
between right and wrong.

00:38:34.170 --> 00:38:37.480
This is not organic impairment
of knowing the rules.

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:40.800
This is organic impairment of
being able to follow the rules.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:44.500
And it is extraordinary
what this one feature

00:38:44.500 --> 00:38:48.040
of what the frontal cortex does,
the difference between knowing

00:38:48.040 --> 00:38:50.480
that there is a difference,
and being able to

00:38:50.480 --> 00:38:52.790
activate this pathway
instead of that.

00:38:52.790 --> 00:38:56.930
This is hugely, hugely
challenging in the courts.

00:38:56.930 --> 00:38:59.800
At the time that Hinckley
attempted to kill Reagan,

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:01.580
every single state
in the country

00:39:01.580 --> 00:39:03.850
that had a McNaughton
ruling in place-- yeah?

00:39:03.850 --> 00:39:06.048
So for those people that
just have the damage

00:39:06.048 --> 00:39:07.833
and know the rules,
would they cover up

00:39:07.833 --> 00:39:10.411
the tracks in court case so
they would be deemed not worthy

00:39:10.411 --> 00:39:12.480
of the McNaughton rule?

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:18.240
OK, yeah, would fail the
McNaughton ruling, absolutely,

00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:20.841
because they know the difference
between right and wrong.

00:39:20.841 --> 00:39:22.299
So they would carry
out the action,

00:39:22.299 --> 00:39:24.900
then realize it was
wrong, so try and hide it?

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:26.010
Yeah, exactly.

00:39:26.010 --> 00:39:28.870
Or if they're disturbed
enough-- OK, for our purposes,

00:39:28.870 --> 00:39:30.870
yes, the person will
know the difference

00:39:30.870 --> 00:39:32.000
between right and wrong.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.040
But they still cannot
regulate their behavior.

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:37.050
And this is a huge problem.

00:39:37.050 --> 00:39:39.490
What you wind up seeing
is the McNaughton rule

00:39:39.490 --> 00:39:42.440
has generally been accepted in
most states in this country.

00:39:42.440 --> 00:39:46.840
At the time that the Reagan
assassination attempt was made,

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:50.240
federal criminal rulings
had McNaughton ruling in it.

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:51.960
Almost all the states
had McNaughton.

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:55.010
And something, about
10 or 11 of them,

00:39:55.010 --> 00:39:59.890
also had organic impairment of
volitional control recognizing

00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:01.440
realms of frontal damage.

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:03.020
And what was very
interesting was

00:40:03.020 --> 00:40:05.990
in the aftermath of Hinckley
being found criminally

00:40:05.990 --> 00:40:08.660
insane instead of
guilty, there were

00:40:08.660 --> 00:40:12.920
these neanderthal bellowings
all over the country, editorials

00:40:12.920 --> 00:40:16.060
everywhere, about how Hinckley
had gotten away with it.

00:40:16.060 --> 00:40:19.520
Within a month, the
federal government Congress

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.170
revoked the ability to
have a McNaughton ruling

00:40:22.170 --> 00:40:25.160
in any federal criminal trial.

00:40:25.160 --> 00:40:27.160
The vast majority of
states in this country,

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:30.080
their legislatures
promptly leapt into action

00:40:30.080 --> 00:40:31.520
to repeal McNaughton.

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:35.040
And along the way, I think
in all but one or two states,

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:37.190
the volitional
impairment rulings

00:40:37.190 --> 00:40:38.860
went down the tubes also.

00:40:38.860 --> 00:40:40.960
And at this point,
the vast majority

00:40:40.960 --> 00:40:44.300
of states in this country, you
could have your frontal cortex

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:46.820
blown out of the water and
you've got one half neuron

00:40:46.820 --> 00:40:48.040
still functioning there.

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:50.920
And that is not relevant
in a court of law--

00:40:50.920 --> 00:40:54.370
an area that desperately,
desperately needs some reform.

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:57.510
To give you a sense of how
bizarre this could look,

00:40:57.510 --> 00:40:59.530
this dissociation
here between knowing

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:01.390
the difference between
right and wrong

00:41:01.390 --> 00:41:04.130
and being able to
regulate your behavior,

00:41:04.130 --> 00:41:07.520
this is what it would look like
in terms of criminal behavior

00:41:07.520 --> 00:41:09.300
with frontal cortical damage.

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:10.970
And, bizarrely,
this was actually

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:13.560
a law case I was involved
with some years ago,

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:15.680
where this was an
individual who had just

00:41:15.680 --> 00:41:18.620
been convicted of his
eighth and ninth murders.

00:41:18.620 --> 00:41:20.770
And this was a serial murderer.

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:24.690
And he was like a nightmare
beyond imagination,

00:41:24.690 --> 00:41:26.460
what this man was.

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:28.790
And this eighth and
ninth one had just

00:41:28.790 --> 00:41:33.760
been two boys he had abducted,
kept captive for a week,

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:38.860
sexually raped, sexually
mutilated, then strangled.

00:41:38.860 --> 00:41:40.770
And this was number
eight and nine.

00:41:40.770 --> 00:41:43.260
And he had been brought
out of a maximum security

00:41:43.260 --> 00:41:46.730
prison in Florida, were
we serving a whole bunch

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:48.170
of other life sentences.

00:41:48.170 --> 00:41:49.839
And this was a case
down in San Diego

00:41:49.839 --> 00:41:51.380
that he was brought
out for that one.

00:41:51.380 --> 00:41:54.610
And the defense consisted of
three minutes of the defense

00:41:54.610 --> 00:41:57.020
attorneys getting up and
saying, yes, he did it.

00:41:57.020 --> 00:41:58.210
He absolutely did it.

00:41:58.210 --> 00:41:59.480
This was the defense.

00:41:59.480 --> 00:42:02.300
So this was now in the
penalty phase deciding,

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:04.360
was this person going to
get the death penalty?

00:42:04.360 --> 00:42:06.730
Or was he going to
get life in prison

00:42:06.730 --> 00:42:08.340
without the chance for parole?

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:10.170
And the relevant
thing about him was

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:13.610
when he was six years old he had
had a massive car accident that

00:42:13.610 --> 00:42:15.340
destroyed his frontal cortex.

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:18.230
He spent two months in
a coma, no prior history

00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:22.080
of anti-social behavior, no
family history of any of it.

00:42:22.080 --> 00:42:25.960
Came out of it extremely
behaviorally disinhibited.

00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:29.420
By age 11, he had assaulted his
first individual, first murder

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:32.970
by age 13-- a completely
broken machine.

00:42:32.970 --> 00:42:35.340
Here's what behavior
looks like in somebody

00:42:35.340 --> 00:42:37.750
with no frontal
cortex in this realm.

00:42:37.750 --> 00:42:39.580
One of the things he
also did, in addition

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:42.420
to his string of murders,
were kidnapping, and rape,

00:42:42.420 --> 00:42:44.500
and aggravated
assault. And this was

00:42:44.500 --> 00:42:48.010
one woman who had managed to,
fortunately, survive this.

00:42:48.010 --> 00:42:50.810
And she'd been abducted
by him, where he took her

00:42:50.810 --> 00:42:53.650
to his apartment and kept
her there for a week,

00:42:53.650 --> 00:42:56.560
repeatedly raping her,
beating her senseless, days

00:42:56.560 --> 00:42:58.150
and days of this going on.

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:01.750
And, eventually, whatever it
is that shifted in him shifted.

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:05.410
He had, of course, her wallet in
the process of kidnapping her,

00:43:05.410 --> 00:43:07.280
and seeing her name,
where she lived,

00:43:07.280 --> 00:43:11.190
he finally says, OK, time to
go, bundles her into his car,

00:43:11.190 --> 00:43:12.750
and drive her home.

00:43:12.750 --> 00:43:16.420
And as he lets her out, he
says, I had a really good time.

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:17.560
I hope you did too.

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:18.740
Here's my phone number.

00:43:18.740 --> 00:43:22.650
Maybe we can get together again
sometime, and drives away.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:25.960
And no surprise, he was
arrested within an hour or so,

00:43:25.960 --> 00:43:28.940
and eventually sort of
pinned to a whole bunch

00:43:28.940 --> 00:43:29.830
of these other ones.

00:43:29.830 --> 00:43:33.380
This is what it looks like when
you've got no frontal cortex.

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:37.050
What's interesting there is
he's obviously made no attempt

00:43:37.050 --> 00:43:38.290
to cover his tracks.

00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:41.370
He was able to verbalize
some of these rules,

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:43.100
and say it was inappropriate.

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:46.940
And he was able even to be told
the specifics of his own case

00:43:46.940 --> 00:43:49.080
with other names used,
and be able to say,

00:43:49.080 --> 00:43:51.420
whoa, that's not
something you should do.

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:52.680
That against the law.

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:56.210
At these junctures, though,
completely going off the rails.

00:43:56.210 --> 00:43:59.070
He had an interesting
combination, though,

00:43:59.070 --> 00:44:00.700
which is that there
were some elements

00:44:00.700 --> 00:44:05.000
of the difference between
right and wrong aspect of it.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:08.730
The fact that he had his frontal
cortex damage so early in life,

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:13.130
what you tend to see is
around age 5 or 6 or younger,

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:16.790
the person tends to never quite
incorporate the rules either.

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:18.700
It's not till you
get-- say, adults

00:44:18.700 --> 00:44:20.160
who get frontal
damage that you get

00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:25.740
the absolutely pure dissociation
between this is not OK to do.

00:44:25.740 --> 00:44:27.520
This is a wrong thing to do.

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:28.860
I am not going to do it.

00:44:28.860 --> 00:44:30.260
And then goes and does it.

00:44:30.260 --> 00:44:33.060
He, instead, had this much
more mixed case there.

00:44:33.060 --> 00:44:35.370
When you get the frontal
damage around ages five,

00:44:35.370 --> 00:44:37.620
or six, or younger,
you get what is now

00:44:37.620 --> 00:44:40.000
termed acquired sociopothy.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.800
You don't do a great
job of incorporating

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:44.100
the rules themselves.

00:44:44.100 --> 00:44:45.850
And you certainly
can't act on it.

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:47.990
So this is what it
looks like with someone

00:44:47.990 --> 00:44:51.980
who is that broken in
this part of the brain.

00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:55.475
Ironic ending, first
jury was hungry.

00:44:55.475 --> 00:44:58.740
We got one person to hold
out for organic impairment

00:44:58.740 --> 00:45:01.070
and give him life
without parole.

00:45:01.070 --> 00:45:02.190
So that was a mistrial.

00:45:02.190 --> 00:45:04.689
And second jury went through
the whole thing all over again.

00:45:04.689 --> 00:45:07.390
And it took them three hours
to give him the death penalty.

00:45:07.390 --> 00:45:11.140
So what's very
interesting there is,

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:14.410
like, 25% of men
on death row have

00:45:14.410 --> 00:45:18.430
a history of concussive trauma
to their frontal cortex--

00:45:18.430 --> 00:45:20.710
really, really interesting.

00:45:20.710 --> 00:45:25.020
But now we begin to see some
of those if-then clauses.

00:45:25.020 --> 00:45:27.870
Here's another individual with
a history of frontal damage.

00:45:27.870 --> 00:45:30.530
And this is a relative of
a close friend of mine.

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:32.810
And this was someone who
when he was being born

00:45:32.810 --> 00:45:34.580
there was a birth complication.

00:45:34.580 --> 00:45:37.080
And they had to use calipers,
and something slipped,

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:38.580
and caused frontal damage.

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:41.380
And frontally disinhibited.

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:45.200
This is an individual who is now
an adult who is unconstrained

00:45:45.200 --> 00:45:47.130
by the laws of society.

00:45:47.130 --> 00:45:50.730
This is an individual who
cannot regulate his behavior.

00:45:50.730 --> 00:45:51.830
What does he do?

00:45:51.830 --> 00:45:53.780
Whenever there's
family get-togethers,

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:57.190
he plays the piano way
longer than anybody else

00:45:57.190 --> 00:45:58.250
wants to listen to.

00:45:58.250 --> 00:46:01.040
He can't pick up the cues
that everybody has had enough

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:02.510
and wants to go eat dinner.

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:04.130
Well, that was great.

00:46:04.130 --> 00:46:06.400
I think the pot roast is
getting a little cold by now.

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:07.524
Wasn't that great everyone?

00:46:07.524 --> 00:46:10.210
Wasn't that-- and
just keeps, oh my God.

00:46:10.210 --> 00:46:11.800
He's out of control.

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:14.420
No less frontal damage
than this guy did.

00:46:14.420 --> 00:46:16.120
So here we have this puzzle.

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.110
We do not have the simple
machine output there,

00:46:19.110 --> 00:46:21.960
of, oh, massive frontal
damage, this person

00:46:21.960 --> 00:46:23.280
is a serial murderer.

00:46:23.280 --> 00:46:24.990
Massive frontal
damage, this person

00:46:24.990 --> 00:46:27.590
plays Scott Joplin
for hours and hours

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:30.630
until even his grandmother
can't stay in the room anymore.

00:46:30.630 --> 00:46:31.890
What's the difference?

00:46:31.890 --> 00:46:34.900
I think we begin to see
some of our if-then clauses

00:46:34.900 --> 00:46:36.200
perhaps relevant.

00:46:36.200 --> 00:46:39.520
The Scott Joplin playing one,
upper middle class family,

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:41.460
tremendous family support.

00:46:41.460 --> 00:46:43.470
This guy coming from
a family anything

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:48.010
but that, we begin to see the,
if you have no frontal cortex

00:46:48.010 --> 00:46:51.530
but you have tremendous
amounts of family support, lots

00:46:51.530 --> 00:46:54.370
of opportunities, blah, blah,
it is going to look different

00:46:54.370 --> 00:46:56.510
than the massive case of it.

00:46:56.510 --> 00:46:59.640
OK, so now looking
at that, what we see

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:01.640
is there's just a
couple of states

00:47:01.640 --> 00:47:03.637
and the couple of juries
in this country that

00:47:03.637 --> 00:47:05.470
could deal with the
implications of somebody

00:47:05.470 --> 00:47:08.600
having 99% of their
frontal cortex destroyed.

00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:11.690
All you need to do to see the
problem we're up against is,

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:13.180
what happens if
you've got somebody

00:47:13.180 --> 00:47:18.170
who's got 97% of their frontal
cortex, destroyed or 94%,

00:47:18.170 --> 00:47:18.980
or 85?

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:22.690
Or finally in our realm, where
we all just have different

00:47:22.690 --> 00:47:23.660
sized ones.

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:26.920
And the person next to you
has 5% more synapses there,

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:30.560
or 3% fewer re-uptake
pumps, or whatever.

00:47:30.560 --> 00:47:34.200
That is beginning to get into a
realm that is very challenging.

