00:51:10.887 --> 00:51:11.970
in the middle of dreaming.

00:51:11.970 --> 00:51:15.260
And, suddenly, that seems like
a wonderfully prudent thing

00:51:15.260 --> 00:51:17.840
to be doing with yourself
in the middle of a dream.

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:21.030
That's when the frontal
cortex is least active.

00:51:21.030 --> 00:51:23.770
OK, so now frontal
cortex, looking

00:51:23.770 --> 00:51:26.060
at one of its most
distinctive, interesting things

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:28.490
about its function,
its development.

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:31.065
When does it
develop after birth?

00:51:31.065 --> 00:51:32.690
And I think what I've
already mentioned

00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:35.230
is the frontal
cortex is interesting

00:51:35.230 --> 00:51:39.700
because it's the last part of
your brain to fully develop.

00:51:39.700 --> 00:51:42.880
It is the last part of
your brain to fully form

00:51:42.880 --> 00:51:45.650
all of the myelin on its axons.

00:51:45.650 --> 00:51:48.560
It's the last part to get
its full large complement

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:51.750
of synapses, and branching
connections, and such.

00:51:51.750 --> 00:51:54.250
It's the last part of
the brain to develop.

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:58.360
When does the frontal cortex, on
the average, completely mature,

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:00.310
go online for the first time?

00:52:00.310 --> 00:52:05.100
Around age 25, which
is astonishing,

00:52:05.100 --> 00:52:08.020
which among other things
should be reckoned

00:52:08.020 --> 00:52:10.490
in the context that,
probably, all sorts of you

00:52:10.490 --> 00:52:13.940
guys still have a whole lot
more myelin to lay down there

00:52:13.940 --> 00:52:15.170
in the frontal cortex.

00:52:15.170 --> 00:52:17.920
It is the last part of the
brain to fully develop.

00:52:17.920 --> 00:52:21.270
Some immediate implications
of that-- if it

00:52:21.270 --> 00:52:24.000
is the last part of the
brain to develop, it is,

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.010
by definition, the
part of the brain

00:52:26.010 --> 00:52:28.480
least constrained by genes.

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:32.280
And it is the part of the brain
most sculpted by environment

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:35.510
and experience, which is
real interesting, given

00:52:35.510 --> 00:52:38.760
that it is the most definedly
human part of the brain.

00:52:38.760 --> 00:52:42.010
So frontal cortical development
in kids-- what we've already

00:52:42.010 --> 00:52:46.010
heard is by age 5 or
younger, get frontal damage,

00:52:46.010 --> 00:52:48.020
and you get this
acquired sociopathy.

00:52:48.020 --> 00:52:51.325
You don't get as clear of a
disassociation between you

00:52:51.325 --> 00:52:54.370
know what the rules are, you
simply can't carry them out.

00:52:54.370 --> 00:52:57.250
It's more of a mixed
bag at that point.

00:52:57.250 --> 00:52:59.890
Frontal development after
that-- the frontal cortex

00:52:59.890 --> 00:53:02.870
works in a very interesting,
perfectly logical way

00:53:02.870 --> 00:53:05.260
in teenagers, as follows.

00:53:05.260 --> 00:53:07.350
When you look at
frontal activity,

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:08.940
and the extent to
which it is being

00:53:08.940 --> 00:53:12.060
driven by dopamine with one
of these brain scanners,

00:53:12.060 --> 00:53:14.730
take an adult, and
take a teenager.

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:17.720
And they each have circumstances
where they're doing some task

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:18.990
and they get a reward.

00:53:18.990 --> 00:53:21.270
And some of the time,
they get a smaller reward

00:53:21.270 --> 00:53:23.520
than they think they deserve
from the amount of effort

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:24.270
they put in.

00:53:24.270 --> 00:53:27.710
And some of the time, they get
an unexpectedly large reward.

00:53:27.710 --> 00:53:30.920
Circumstance where the
individual gets a bigger reward

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:34.210
than anticipated,
dopamine goes up in adults

00:53:34.210 --> 00:53:37.080
and drives frontal metabolism
to a certain extent.

00:53:37.080 --> 00:53:40.670
Dopamine goes up much
higher in the teenager.

00:53:40.670 --> 00:53:44.120
Now a circumstance where the
task is being carried out.

00:53:44.120 --> 00:53:46.480
And you don't get the reward.

00:53:46.480 --> 00:53:48.790
Dopamine goes down in the
adult, frontal metabolism

00:53:48.790 --> 00:53:49.820
goes down a bit.

00:53:49.820 --> 00:53:53.200
Dopamine goes down much
more in the teenager.

00:53:53.200 --> 00:53:56.070
The gyrations are
much more extreme.

00:53:56.070 --> 00:54:00.200
The dopamine-driven metabolic
changes in the frontal cortex

00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:02.950
are more dramatically
large for reward,

00:54:02.950 --> 00:54:05.860
are more dramatically
having the floor fall out

00:54:05.860 --> 00:54:08.880
under it for lack of
reward, for disappointment.

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:11.970
It's a system that is
simply less regulated.

00:54:11.970 --> 00:54:14.700
And this, this fact that the
frontal cortex is the last

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:18.070
maturing part of the brain, had
to do with one of the wisest

00:54:18.070 --> 00:54:20.360
things the Supreme Court
has done in a long time,

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:23.470
which was about 10 years ago,
when they made a ruling that

00:54:23.470 --> 00:54:26.340
individuals who
are under age 18,

00:54:26.340 --> 00:54:28.770
when they carry out
a capital crime,

00:54:28.770 --> 00:54:31.880
you cannot have the death
penalty applied to someone

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:35.130
for a crime they did
between ages 16 and 18,

00:54:35.130 --> 00:54:38.440
because explicitly stated
in the court decision,

00:54:38.440 --> 00:54:41.720
the brain and the regulatory
areas of the brain are not

00:54:41.720 --> 00:54:45.830
fully mature at that point--
the most neurologically informed

00:54:45.830 --> 00:54:47.800
the Supreme Court has
been in a long time.

00:54:47.800 --> 00:54:51.060
Again, the McNaughton rule--
the McNaughton rule, which

00:54:51.060 --> 00:54:53.940
is the backbone of the criminal
defense and legal system

00:54:53.940 --> 00:54:59.070
in this country, is based on
170-year-old neurobiology.

00:54:59.070 --> 00:55:02.216
So this was a major leap
forward in jurisprudence

00:55:02.216 --> 00:55:04.590
meets neurobiology in this
country with the Supreme Court

00:55:04.590 --> 00:55:05.160
ruling.

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:08.080
Of course, what
one might ask is,

00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:10.630
so what exactly happens in
the brain on the morning

00:55:10.630 --> 00:55:12.800
of your 18th birthday
that now makes

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:15.444
it OK to put you to death,
where the science simply

00:55:15.444 --> 00:55:16.110
doesn't back it?

00:55:16.110 --> 00:55:19.600
But at least that recognition,
the Supreme Court actually

00:55:19.600 --> 00:55:23.090
dealing with the fact that
a 17-year-old does not have

00:55:23.090 --> 00:55:25.930
a normal frontal cortex yet.

00:55:25.930 --> 00:55:28.330
What else goes on?

00:55:28.330 --> 00:55:31.210
Thus, by the time you get a
fully online frontal cortex,

00:55:31.210 --> 00:55:34.800
around age 25 or so, one of
the truly depressing things

00:55:34.800 --> 00:55:37.540
out the other end of it
is the frontal cortex

00:55:37.540 --> 00:55:42.790
is the third most vulnerable
brain region to normal aging--

00:55:42.790 --> 00:55:43.790
bummer.

00:55:43.790 --> 00:55:45.140
That is a drag.

00:55:45.140 --> 00:55:48.230
What that winds up meaning is
you have spectacular impulse

00:55:48.230 --> 00:55:50.070
control for about
three and a half weeks

00:55:50.070 --> 00:55:51.580
on your 25th birthday.

00:55:51.580 --> 00:55:53.356
And it's all
downhill from there.

00:55:53.356 --> 00:55:55.730
There's a motor system in the
brain called the substantia

00:55:55.730 --> 00:55:59.300
nigra which loses most of
its neurons with aging.

00:55:59.300 --> 00:56:01.520
That has something to do
with the tremor of old age,

00:56:01.520 --> 00:56:02.880
Parkinson's disease.

00:56:02.880 --> 00:56:06.310
The hippocampus lose substantial
percentage of its neurons

00:56:06.310 --> 00:56:06.870
with age.

00:56:06.870 --> 00:56:09.350
That has something to do with
some of the memory problems.

00:56:09.350 --> 00:56:12.410
Number three on the list
is the frontal cortex.

00:56:12.410 --> 00:56:15.200
Frontal cortex loses
lots of neurons

00:56:15.200 --> 00:56:16.640
over the course of aging.

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:19.370
And what you see, then,
is all of those tests

00:56:19.370 --> 00:56:22.010
of cognitive function,
of frontal functioning,

00:56:22.010 --> 00:56:24.650
they all have to be
age-adjusted because people

00:56:24.650 --> 00:56:28.670
as they get older have more
trouble doing this, inhibiting

00:56:28.670 --> 00:56:31.590
the over-learned response,
preventing something

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:33.270
from intruding previously.

00:56:33.270 --> 00:56:36.530
There's fewer of these
projections coming in there.

00:56:36.530 --> 00:56:38.470
And what does this
begin to explain?

00:56:38.470 --> 00:56:41.990
This is this whole world
of grandmothers telling you

00:56:41.990 --> 00:56:45.260
exactly how hideous they
think your new hairdo is.

00:56:45.260 --> 00:56:48.560
That's the world of disinhibited
80-year-olds speaking.

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:51.150
And what has always been
the case in that literature,

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:54.940
it has always been interpreted
in a social, psychological

00:56:54.940 --> 00:56:56.710
maturation framework.

00:56:56.710 --> 00:56:59.400
By the time you get
to a certain age,

00:56:59.400 --> 00:57:01.990
you finally accept,
this is who I am.

00:57:01.990 --> 00:57:05.040
I'm not in middle school anymore
just trying to be popular.

00:57:05.040 --> 00:57:07.140
If I need to march to
a different drummer,

00:57:07.140 --> 00:57:09.690
so be it, because I am
at peace with who I am.

00:57:09.690 --> 00:57:10.610
I accept myself.

00:57:10.610 --> 00:57:11.430
It's not that.

00:57:11.430 --> 00:57:12.770
It's the brain damage.

00:57:12.770 --> 00:57:16.320
It's the brain damage that kicks
in at that point, that being

00:57:16.320 --> 00:57:19.190
a feature of normative aging.

00:57:19.190 --> 00:57:22.220
Now, where else do you wind
up seeing abnormalities

00:57:22.220 --> 00:57:23.630
and frontal function?

00:57:23.630 --> 00:57:26.100
Other individuals,
individual differences--

00:57:26.100 --> 00:57:28.750
one personality
style where you see

00:57:28.750 --> 00:57:30.940
elevated frontal metabolism.

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:32.620
And this is people
with what's called

00:57:32.620 --> 00:57:34.910
