But now something interesting.

00:59:17.170 --> 00:59:20.530
You take a sociopath whose
resting metabolic rate

00:59:20.530 --> 00:59:23.680
in the frontal cortex
is lower than normal.

00:59:23.680 --> 00:59:27.480
Now you give them a task
which demands a certain degree

00:59:27.480 --> 00:59:29.070
of frontal function.

00:59:29.070 --> 00:59:32.090
Not, oh, be a law abiding
citizen in society,

00:59:32.090 --> 00:59:34.270
but something like the
tell the months of the year

00:59:34.270 --> 00:59:36.330
backwards as fast as you can go.

00:59:36.330 --> 00:59:38.990
And what you see is
in order to generate

00:59:38.990 --> 00:59:42.060
the same level of
performance, they

00:59:42.060 --> 00:59:44.590
have to activate more
of the frontal cortex

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:45.835
than other people do.

00:59:45.835 --> 00:59:48.980
In other words, under
resting circumstances,

00:59:48.980 --> 00:59:52.480
there is a hypometabolism
in the frontal cortex.

00:59:52.480 --> 00:59:55.990
And in the rare, relatively
unemotional circumstances

00:59:55.990 --> 00:59:59.610
where a sociopath does want to
pull off a lot of regulation

00:59:59.610 --> 01:00:02.280
of behavior, they've got
to recruit a lot more

01:00:02.280 --> 01:00:04.200
of the frontal cortex to do it.

01:00:04.200 --> 01:00:07.040
It takes more work to do.

01:00:07.040 --> 01:00:09.230
Other aspects of
frontal cortex--

01:00:09.230 --> 01:00:12.110
not only are kids not
dealing with a whole lot

01:00:12.110 --> 01:00:13.220
of frontal cortex.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:15.340
Other species are not
dealing with a whole lot

01:00:15.340 --> 01:00:16.600
of frontal cortex.

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:19.670
Again, humans have more
frontal cortex proportionately

01:00:19.670 --> 01:00:21.150
than any other species.

01:00:21.150 --> 01:00:23.400
There is no chimpanzee
on Earth who

01:00:23.400 --> 01:00:26.330
could master the five
M&amp;M, one M&amp;M task.

01:00:26.330 --> 01:00:29.370
And that is regularly used as
a test for frontal function

01:00:29.370 --> 01:00:29.900
on them.

01:00:29.900 --> 01:00:34.010
Chimps cannot do it because it
is simply too tempting to reach

01:00:34.010 --> 01:00:37.950
for the five M&amp;Md
because it's right there.

01:00:37.950 --> 01:00:41.670
Interesting assay of how many
frontal neurons a chimp does

01:00:41.670 --> 01:00:46.320
have, though, which is now
instead of 5 M&amp;Ms and 1 M&amp;M,

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:49.200
five chips of wood
and one chip of wood.

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:53.420
Reach for the five chips
of wood, you get one M&amp;M.

01:00:53.420 --> 01:00:57.480
Reach for the one chip of
wood, you get five M&amp;Ms.

01:00:57.480 --> 01:00:59.080
Every chimp can do it now.

01:00:59.080 --> 01:01:01.350
They can all do it now
because they're just looking

01:01:01.350 --> 01:01:02.591
at these pieces of wood.

01:01:02.591 --> 01:01:04.090
And they can remember,
that's right.

01:01:04.090 --> 01:01:05.540
Don't go for the
five pieces of wood.

01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:06.748
Go for the one piece of wood.

01:01:06.748 --> 01:01:08.720
When it's chocolate,
though, in front of them,

01:01:08.720 --> 01:01:11.290
it's smells so great.

01:01:11.290 --> 01:01:14.110
And how can you expect them
to keep track of the rules?

01:01:14.110 --> 01:01:15.862
And it's just the five.

01:01:15.862 --> 01:01:18.070
And before you know it,
they've done the wrong thing.

01:01:18.070 --> 01:01:20.770
If you take away some
of the viscera of it,

01:01:20.770 --> 01:01:24.210
if you step back sensorially,
if you substitute

01:01:24.210 --> 01:01:27.190
this in your face chocolate
for these little bits of wood,

01:01:27.190 --> 01:01:29.870
chimps on the average have
enough frontal function

01:01:29.870 --> 01:01:33.300
to be able to pull
that task off.

01:01:33.300 --> 01:01:35.330
Kids, again, could
never do this.

01:01:35.330 --> 01:01:38.090
And this is one classic
sort of developmental test.

01:01:38.090 --> 01:01:39.130
You take a kid.

01:01:39.130 --> 01:01:40.390
And they're in a room.

01:01:40.390 --> 01:01:42.080
And you put a marshmallow there.

01:01:42.080 --> 01:01:46.010
And you say, OK, does
people know this one?

01:01:46.010 --> 01:01:49.700
OK, so do people
now know this one?

01:01:49.700 --> 01:01:50.880
OK, so here's what you do.

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:52.130
You put the marshmallow there.

01:01:52.130 --> 01:01:54.132
And you tell the child,
OK, I've got to go out

01:01:54.132 --> 01:01:55.340
of the room for a little bit.

01:01:55.340 --> 01:01:57.214
You can have a marshmallow
whenever you want.

01:01:57.214 --> 01:01:59.960
But if you haven't had it
by the time I come back,

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:01.370
you can have two marshmallows.

01:02:01.370 --> 01:02:03.670
In other words,
how many synapses

01:02:03.670 --> 01:02:05.850
do you have in your
frontal cortex?

01:02:05.850 --> 01:02:08.740
Because that is
spectacularly predictive

01:02:08.740 --> 01:02:11.230
of frontal metabolism
in these kids.

01:02:11.230 --> 01:02:15.160
How long can they hold out
doing the harder thing that

01:02:15.160 --> 01:02:16.570
gets more of a reward?

01:02:16.570 --> 01:02:18.310
What those studies
also were showing

01:02:18.310 --> 01:02:20.850
is the length of time
a kid could hold out

01:02:20.850 --> 01:02:23.370
on the marshmallow test
when they're five years old

01:02:23.370 --> 01:02:27.410
is predictive of SAT
scores many years later,

01:02:27.410 --> 01:02:31.620
is predictive of all sorts
of aspects of the trajectory

01:02:31.620 --> 01:02:34.520
of that frontal development.

01:02:34.520 --> 01:02:37.390
Here's an even better assay
for frontal function in a kid.

01:02:37.390 --> 01:02:40.287
And this one, I think this
is even more informative

01:02:40.287 --> 01:02:41.370
than the marshmallow test.

01:02:41.370 --> 01:02:42.350
Here's what you do.

01:02:42.350 --> 01:02:43.600
You've got your five-year-old.

01:02:43.600 --> 01:02:46.310
And you play hide
and seek with them.

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:49.160
And the deal is you're
the one who counts first

01:02:49.160 --> 01:02:50.160
while they go and hide.

01:02:50.160 --> 01:02:51.870
And what you do is
you finish counting.

01:02:51.870 --> 01:02:54.850
And then you loudly,
excitedly say, here I come.

01:02:54.850 --> 01:02:55.351
Here I come.

01:02:55.351 --> 01:02:56.225
I'm going to get you.

01:02:56.225 --> 01:02:56.880
Here I come.

01:02:56.880 --> 01:02:58.150
Oh, where are you?

01:02:58.150 --> 01:03:01.070
And then they instantly say,
right here under the piano,

01:03:01.070 --> 01:03:03.380
because they don't have
enough frontal neurons to keep

01:03:03.380 --> 01:03:04.607
themselves from saying that.

01:03:04.607 --> 01:03:06.690
They can't stop themselves
from saying, here I am.

01:03:06.690 --> 01:03:08.000
Here I am, falling for that.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:09.250
Now, they switch.

01:03:09.250 --> 01:03:10.730
And it's their turn to count.

01:03:10.730 --> 01:03:11.450
And they count.

01:03:11.450 --> 01:03:12.480
You count up to 10.

01:03:12.480 --> 01:03:15.940
And they go 7, 8, 9,
10, 11, 12, 13, 14,

01:03:15.940 --> 01:03:18.460
because they're so excited
to have discovered recently

01:03:18.460 --> 01:03:23.250
there's all these numbers, that
why not count all of them off?

01:03:23.250 --> 01:03:26.450
And they've long forgotten
you're supposed to stop at 10.

01:03:26.450 --> 01:03:28.630
They can't inhibit
that response.

01:03:28.630 --> 01:03:31.810
This is what frontal function
looks like in a kid--

01:03:31.810 --> 01:03:34.680
so marshmallow tests
and hide and seek tests.

01:03:34.680 --> 01:03:37.220
How's this, though, for
taking that charming world

01:03:37.220 --> 01:03:39.680
of five-year-old
regulation and putting it

01:03:39.680 --> 01:03:43.440
into a much more depressing
developmental context?

01:03:43.440 --> 01:03:49.200
Studies by now showing at age 5,
already kindergarten-aged kids,

01:03:49.200 --> 01:03:52.660
there is a relationship between
your socioeconomic status

01:03:52.660 --> 01:03:55.240
and the thickness of
your frontal cortex

01:03:55.240 --> 01:03:57.910
and its resting metabolic rate.

01:03:57.910 --> 01:03:59.420
What's the part
of the brain that

01:03:59.420 --> 01:04:01.690
has some of the highest
levels of receptors

01:04:01.690 --> 01:04:03.410
for glucocorticoids?

01:04:03.410 --> 01:04:04.870
The frontal cortex.

01:04:04.870 --> 01:04:08.060
What do glucocorticoids
do to the frontal cortex?

01:04:08.060 --> 01:04:10.200
They atrophy neurons there.

01:04:10.200 --> 01:04:12.240
So what you are
already seeing is,

01:04:12.240 --> 01:04:15.450
get yourself an unfortunate,
imprudent decision

01:04:15.450 --> 01:04:18.300
in terms of which family
you got yourself born into.

01:04:18.300 --> 01:04:20.630
And be raised with
the stress of poverty.

01:04:20.630 --> 01:04:24.380
And by age 5, already there
are socioeconomic differences

01:04:24.380 --> 01:04:27.570
in the size and the activity
of the frontal cortex.

01:04:27.570 --> 01:04:30.580
And that is, I think, one
of those factoids that

01:04:30.580 --> 01:04:33.830
should have people rioting
at the barricades in terms

01:04:33.830 --> 01:04:38.010
of how screwed you are, how
early on in life in the most

01:04:38.010 --> 01:04:41.460
straight forwardly
neurobiological way by some

01:04:41.460 --> 01:04:45.370
of these oddities of
experience and bad luck.

01:04:45.370 --> 01:04:49.640
OK, so looking finally at the
frontal cortex-- one thing

01:04:49.640 --> 01:04:54.120
to ask at the end of the day
is, so, frontal disinhibition?

01:04:54.120 --> 01:04:57.490
Why don't you see with people
with massive frontal damage,

01:04:57.490 --> 01:04:59.610
instead of them becoming
serial murderers,

01:04:59.610 --> 01:05:03.060
why don't they become like
serial people getting married?

01:05:03.060 --> 01:05:06.530
Why aren't they serial standing
on street corners giving away

01:05:06.530 --> 01:05:09.540
their money and announcing
their love to the whole world,

01:05:09.540 --> 01:05:12.890
and doing equally disinhibited
things in that realm?

01:05:12.890 --> 01:05:13.890
It's not clear.

01:05:13.890 --> 01:05:17.910
It's not clear why this is
so much more tightly involved

01:05:17.910 --> 01:05:21.150
in regulation of stuff
going on in the amygdala.

01:05:21.150 --> 01:05:24.080
OK, so as implied,
though, by this arrow,

01:05:24.080 --> 01:05:26.730
it is not one direction
of inputs there.

01:05:26.730 --> 01:05:28.160
It is bidirectional.

01:05:28.160 --> 01:05:32.000
What you also see is a lot of
ways in which the amygdala can

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:33.970
regulate the frontal cortex.

01:05:33.970 --> 01:05:36.350
And what you already can
guess is the projection

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:39.600
from the frontal cortex to
the amygdala is inhibitory.

01:05:39.600 --> 01:05:42.720
The projection from the
amygdala to the frontal cortex

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:44.260
is inhibitory.

01:05:44.260 --> 01:05:46.910
The frontal cortex is
trying to get the amygdala

01:05:46.910 --> 01:05:48.680
to restrain itself.

01:05:48.680 --> 01:05:51.160
The amygdala is trying
to get the frontal cortex

01:05:51.160 --> 01:05:53.000
to stop sermonizing at it.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:56.160
And what you wind up seeing
is in rats, in primates,

01:05:56.160 --> 01:05:59.160
and humans there is
an inverse correlation

01:05:59.160 --> 01:06:02.480
under resting conditions
between the metabolic level

01:06:02.480 --> 01:06:04.850
in the amygdala and
the frontal cortex.

01:06:04.850 --> 01:06:08.310
They move in opposition.

01:06:08.310 --> 01:06:11.540
And what you see is, what
are the circumstances where,

01:06:11.540 --> 01:06:15.230
in effect, the amygdala is going
crazy enough to be silencing

01:06:15.230 --> 01:06:16.620
the frontal cortex?

01:06:16.620 --> 01:06:18.170
That's the world
in which you are

01:06:18.170 --> 01:06:22.230
making astonishingly bad
decisions about things

01:06:22.230 --> 01:06:24.600
during moments of great
duress and arousal

01:06:24.600 --> 01:06:26.750
that you spend the rest
of your life regretting.

01:06:26.750 --> 01:06:30.780
That's the world of the amygdala
getting very inaccurate, rapid

01:06:30.780 --> 01:06:34.870
fire information, and being able
to silence the frontal cortex.

01:06:34.870 --> 01:06:38.730
And then out comes behavior
that is really unregulated.

01:06:38.730 --> 01:06:41.380
The frontal cortex and
the amygdala, in a sense,

01:06:41.380 --> 01:06:46.150
constantly wrestling in
terms of their reciprocity.

01:06:46.150 --> 01:06:48.950
So what happens when
somebody has learned

01:06:48.950 --> 01:06:50.390
to be afraid of something?

01:06:50.390 --> 01:06:53.740
And slowly, over time, they
learn that, in fact, this thing

01:06:53.740 --> 01:06:55.300
is not fearful?

01:06:55.300 --> 01:06:59.120
They habituate to this
fear-conditioned response.

01:06:59.120 --> 01:07:02.060
They habituate to yoking.

01:07:02.060 --> 01:07:04.700
This buzzer means I'm
going to get a shock.

01:07:04.700 --> 01:07:06.600
They extinguish the behavior.

01:07:06.600 --> 01:07:08.380
That's the term given for that.

01:07:08.380 --> 01:07:11.660
You gradually see the amygdala
activates less and less.

01:07:11.660 --> 01:07:13.479
Oh, play the buzzer,
play the tone,

01:07:13.479 --> 01:07:15.770
that you've been conditioned
to associate with a shock.

01:07:15.770 --> 01:07:17.560
Amygdala goes crazy.

01:07:17.560 --> 01:07:19.810
No shock this time,
do the buzzer again,

01:07:19.810 --> 01:07:21.560
no shock, not quite as active.

01:07:21.560 --> 01:07:25.010
Next time, not quite as active,
and it slowly habituates away.

01:07:25.010 --> 01:07:27.600
Destroy the frontal
cortex, and the amygdala

01:07:27.600 --> 01:07:30.820
never habituates to
a learned response,

01:07:30.820 --> 01:07:34.350
a fear-conditioned response
which is no longer fearful.

01:07:34.350 --> 01:07:37.200
It can't learn to
stop being afraid--

01:07:37.200 --> 01:07:40.750
so another realm of this
reciprocal inhibitory

01:07:40.750 --> 01:07:46.430
relationship between the
frontal cortex and the amygdala.

01:07:46.430 --> 01:07:50.030
OK, final bit here in terms
of their interactions--

01:07:50.030 --> 01:07:53.410
the easiest way to frame it
is, each inhibits the other.

01:07:53.410 --> 01:07:55.000
They work reciprocally.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:58.490
There are circumstances, though,
where both the frontal cortex

01:07:58.490 --> 01:08:02.030
and the amygdala will activate
because all you have to think

01:08:02.030 --> 01:08:04.850
are of some circumstances
where whatever

01:08:04.850 --> 01:08:08.770
your cultural conditioning is,
doing the harder thing, which

01:08:08.770 --> 01:08:11.980
is the right thing, is
also the scarier thing.

01:08:11.980 --> 01:08:14.540
Just think what it takes to
have somebody blow a whistle.

01:08:14.540 --> 01:08:17.729
And you leap up over the top
of your trench in World War I.

01:08:17.729 --> 01:08:19.810
And you're going
to be dead 10 steps

01:08:19.810 --> 01:08:22.029
into running towards
the other trench line.

01:08:22.029 --> 01:08:24.279
At some point,
the frontal cortex

01:08:24.279 --> 01:08:27.840
is, in fact, stimulating
the amygdala very strongly

01:08:27.840 --> 01:08:29.490
to produce its behaviors.

01:08:29.490 --> 01:08:32.240
That's showing a circumstance
where that is, indeed,

01:08:32.240 --> 01:08:33.160
the harder behavior.

01:08:33.160 --> 01:08:37.200
It is simplifying to say that
they always work in opposition.

01:08:37.200 --> 01:08:39.399
But as a general rule,
that's happening.

01:08:39.399 --> 01:08:42.689
OK, what this allows us
do now is step back a bit

01:08:42.689 --> 01:08:45.430
and now look at another
brain region, one

01:08:45.430 --> 01:08:48.270
which is in effect
working in opposition

01:08:48.270 --> 01:08:52.199
to the amygdala in another
realm, which is the septum.

01:08:52.199 --> 01:08:53.720
And you remember the septum.

01:08:53.720 --> 01:08:57.229
The hippocampus sends its
loop through the fornix

01:08:57.229 --> 01:08:58.710
down to that septum thing.

01:08:58.710 --> 01:09:02.100
In some manner, the septum
inhibits aggression.

01:09:02.100 --> 01:09:04.760
In the same way that,
simplistically, the amygdala

01:09:04.760 --> 01:09:07.590
mediates it, the exact
same sort of evidence,

01:09:07.590 --> 01:09:10.960
lesion studies, stimulation
studies, recording studies.

01:09:10.960 --> 01:09:13.100
For reasons I don't
fully understand,

01:09:13.100 --> 01:09:15.460
the septum has never
been really a hot spot

01:09:15.460 --> 01:09:16.790
for a lot of research.

01:09:16.790 --> 01:09:19.680
Nonetheless, it, in some
ways, works in opposition

01:09:19.680 --> 01:09:20.920
to the amygdala.

01:09:20.920 --> 01:09:23.410
You could now sit with
one of those circuit

01:09:23.410 --> 01:09:26.800
diagrams of the limbic system
seeing who's connecting to who.

01:09:26.800 --> 01:09:29.060
And you could see
what sort of wiring

01:09:29.060 --> 01:09:31.090
there must be for
the septum to try

01:09:31.090 --> 01:09:35.080
to silence the amygdala, what
the circuitry there would be.

01:09:35.080 --> 01:09:37.810
Back to that limbic rule,
all these limbic structures

01:09:37.810 --> 01:09:39.910
are trying to yell
at the hypothalamus

01:09:39.910 --> 01:09:43.630
and get it to listen to them
and not to the other regions.

01:09:43.630 --> 01:09:45.950
Another area implicated
in aggression--

01:09:45.950 --> 01:09:50.450
the lateral
hypothalamus, subject

01:09:50.450 --> 01:09:53.220
of a huge amount of research
in the 1960s, people

01:09:53.220 --> 01:09:54.470
interested in aggression.

01:09:54.470 --> 01:09:56.984
And then people acted
like ethologists

01:09:56.984 --> 01:09:58.650
and learned the thing
that we've already

01:09:58.650 --> 01:10:02.160
talked about a bit in here,
which is, oh, actually

01:10:02.160 --> 01:10:04.980
the lateral hypothalamus has
nothing to do with aggression.

01:10:04.980 --> 01:10:07.070
It's got to do with
predatory behavior.

01:10:07.070 --> 01:10:10.090
When a rat leaps on a
mouse and shreds it,

01:10:10.090 --> 01:10:11.570
that's not an act of aggression.

01:10:11.570 --> 01:10:13.380
That's an act of foraging.

01:10:13.380 --> 01:10:18.680
Oh, lateral hypothalamus, food
acquisition, not aggression.

01:10:18.680 --> 01:10:21.700
Tons of research in the
'60s went down the tubes

01:10:21.700 --> 01:10:24.600
when people began
to figure that out.

01:10:24.600 --> 01:10:27.670
Now flipping to the other
side of all of this stuff

01:10:27.670 --> 01:10:30.800
rather than the aggression
realm, the empathy realm,

01:10:30.800 --> 01:10:33.870
the compassionate realm-- where
are the structures coming in?

01:10:33.870 --> 01:10:36.450
And we already know
one area from the sex

01:10:36.450 --> 01:10:38.130
lectures that is
pertinent, which

01:10:38.130 --> 01:10:41.230
is the anterior
cingulate, sitting just

01:10:41.230 --> 01:10:42.970
behind the frontal cortex.

01:10:42.970 --> 01:10:45.550
And we already know about some
of the things that it does.

01:10:45.550 --> 01:10:47.540
Remember, that's the
part of the brain,

01:10:47.540 --> 01:10:51.600
somebody pokes your finger, it
activates, along with your pain

01:10:51.600 --> 01:10:53.060
receptor pathways.

01:10:53.060 --> 01:10:56.090
You watch the finger of your
loved on gets poked with a pin,

01:10:56.090 --> 01:10:58.910
anterior cingulate
activates as well.

01:10:58.910 --> 01:11:02.120
That is the part of the brain
where, literally and not just

01:11:02.120 --> 01:11:06.490
metaphorically, you feel the
pain of other individuals.

01:11:06.490 --> 01:11:07.670
How is this?

01:11:07.670 --> 01:11:10.400
Now, a study-- this was done
recently by a guy at Harvard

01:11:10.400 --> 01:11:11.420
named Josh Green.

01:11:11.420 --> 01:11:14.770
What he does is he puts people
in brain scanners, functional

01:11:14.770 --> 01:11:15.470
MRIs.

01:11:15.470 --> 01:11:18.890
And he gives them one of
the great, horrifying moral

01:11:18.890 --> 01:11:21.270
decisions that ever
sort of actually

01:11:21.270 --> 01:11:24.660
occurred in history, which
was the old scenario that

01:11:24.660 --> 01:11:28.140
and a bunch of people are hiding
from the Nazis who are nearby.

01:11:28.140 --> 01:11:30.020
And there is a baby with you.

01:11:30.020 --> 01:11:31.760
And the baby who keeps crying.

01:11:31.760 --> 01:11:33.370
And it is clear
if the baby keeps

01:11:33.370 --> 01:11:35.880
crying you are all going
to be caught and killed.

01:11:35.880 --> 01:11:38.110
Is it OK to smother the child?

01:11:38.110 --> 01:11:40.370
And this wonderfully
hypothetical,

01:11:40.370 --> 01:11:42.590
let's write a doctoral
thesis dissertation

01:11:42.590 --> 01:11:44.620
on this problem
here, was one which

01:11:44.620 --> 01:11:46.810
was a human sort
of decision that

01:11:46.810 --> 01:11:48.900
had to be made endless
number of times.

01:11:48.900 --> 01:11:51.240
What would you do in
that circumstance?

01:11:51.240 --> 01:11:53.260
And what he shows
in these studies

01:11:53.260 --> 01:11:57.610
are that people who activate
the anterior cingulate less

01:11:57.610 --> 01:11:59.930
when they are
contemplating this decision

01:11:59.930 --> 01:12:02.380
are more likely to reach
the decision that it

01:12:02.380 --> 01:12:04.740
is OK to smother the child.

01:12:04.740 --> 01:12:08.730
You see that in these studies,
something about the feeling

01:12:08.730 --> 01:12:11.970
the pain element,
the empathizing,

01:12:11.970 --> 01:12:14.920
something about that,
when it is not as extreme,

01:12:14.920 --> 01:12:17.810
that it is a predictor in these
studies of the individuals

01:12:17.810 --> 01:12:20.030
who will vote for
the smothering.

01:12:20.030 --> 01:12:22.740
All of this has given
rise to this view

01:12:22.740 --> 01:12:25.970
that a lot of what's
happening between the cortex

01:12:25.970 --> 01:12:28.970
and the limbic system is a
whole lot more complicated

01:12:28.970 --> 01:12:32.807
than this old dichotomy
between thought and emotion.

01:12:32.807 --> 01:12:34.140
And the cortex is about thought.

01:12:34.140 --> 01:12:35.910
And the limbic system
is about emotion.

01:12:35.910 --> 01:12:39.000
What is clear is, instead,
they are inseparable.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:40.900
This whole notion
brought up already,

01:12:40.900 --> 01:12:44.400
that Guy Damasio, major figure
in the field, this book of his

01:12:44.400 --> 01:12:46.200
called Descartes'
Error, where he

01:12:46.200 --> 01:12:50.310
goes over Descartes' notion
of the separability of thought

01:12:50.310 --> 01:12:52.720
and emotion, and how in
terms of brain function

01:12:52.720 --> 01:12:54.770
that is not remotely the case.

01:12:54.770 --> 01:12:57.290
In some realms,
you can partially

01:12:57.290 --> 01:13:01.780
separate frontal cortical
function from limbic function.

01:13:01.780 --> 01:13:04.780
One example of this-- and
this was a classic study done

01:13:04.780 --> 01:13:06.397
by that same guy, Josh Green.

01:13:06.397 --> 01:13:08.480
And this was when he was
still a graduate student.

01:13:08.480 --> 01:13:11.430
It involved making use of
people with a brain scanner

01:13:11.430 --> 01:13:13.950
with what's apparently
a classic test

01:13:13.950 --> 01:13:16.140
in, or a classic
puzzle in, philosophy--

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:18.620
the runaway trolley problem.

01:13:18.620 --> 01:13:20.220
Here's the scenario.

01:13:20.220 --> 01:13:22.110
There is a trolley
which is somehow

01:13:22.110 --> 01:13:23.650
broken loose from its brake.

01:13:23.650 --> 01:13:25.490
It is rolling down
the tracks, where

01:13:25.490 --> 01:13:29.180
it is going to roll over
there and kill five people.

01:13:29.180 --> 01:13:31.560
First scenario,
you have a choice.

01:13:31.560 --> 01:13:34.880
You can pull a lever, which
will cause the trolley

01:13:34.880 --> 01:13:36.960
to be diverted onto a
different track, where

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:38.710
it will kill one person.

01:13:38.710 --> 01:13:42.540
Is it OK to pull the lever,
saving these five people,

01:13:42.540 --> 01:13:44.530
and one person getting killed?

01:13:44.530 --> 01:13:47.160
Second scenario, you
have the option--

01:13:47.160 --> 01:13:49.590
you're standing behind
this big beefy person.

01:13:49.590 --> 01:13:52.580
And you can push him onto the
track, where the trolley will

01:13:52.580 --> 01:13:53.810
hit them and kill them.

01:13:53.810 --> 01:13:57.350
But it will stop it from
hitting the five people.

01:13:57.350 --> 01:14:01.200
Are you willing to kill one
person in order to save five?

01:14:01.200 --> 01:14:03.860
And something that is shown
in these studies over and over

01:14:03.860 --> 01:14:08.080
is 75% of people are
willing to pull the lever.

01:14:08.080 --> 01:14:11.640
25% of people or so or
willing with their own hands

01:14:11.640 --> 01:14:13.560
to push somebody onto the track.

01:14:13.560 --> 01:14:16.410
The math, the logic,
is absolutely equal.

01:14:16.410 --> 01:14:18.860
But this is always
interpreted as how

01:14:18.860 --> 01:14:20.730
we make different
sorts of decisions

01:14:20.730 --> 01:14:23.700
when it is a much more
visceral, in your face,

01:14:23.700 --> 01:14:27.020
you are going to have to
push this person to his death

01:14:27.020 --> 01:14:28.870
with your own hands,
versus something

01:14:28.870 --> 01:14:31.850
as impersonal as
pulling a lever sitting

01:14:31.850 --> 01:14:35.200
in a cockpit in a military
base in Las Vegas,

01:14:35.200 --> 01:14:37.360
and killing people on the
other side of the globe.

01:14:37.360 --> 01:14:39.760
How salient, in your face is it?

01:14:39.760 --> 01:14:42.780
You get very
different responses.

01:14:42.780 --> 01:14:45.110
And what Green showed
in his study was,

01:14:45.110 --> 01:14:47.180
have people contemplating
whether or not

01:14:47.180 --> 01:14:50.450
to pull the lever, it's the
cortex that's activating--

01:14:50.450 --> 01:14:52.320
predominantly frontal cortex.

01:14:52.320 --> 01:14:55.420
Have people decide whether or
not to push with their hands,

01:14:55.420 --> 01:14:58.347
it's predominately
limbic activation.

01:14:58.347 --> 01:15:00.430
Another version of this--
this has been researched

01:15:00.430 --> 01:15:02.920
by a guy at Dartmouth named
Oliver Goodenough-- again,

01:15:02.920 --> 01:15:03.990
brain imaging.

01:15:03.990 --> 01:15:06.750
And he is both a neurobiologist
and also on the law

01:15:06.750 --> 01:15:08.040
school faculty there.

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:09.720
And here's the sort
of study he does.

01:15:09.720 --> 01:15:11.780
You will see the
equivalency of it.

01:15:11.780 --> 01:15:13.060
Put people in a scanner.

01:15:13.060 --> 01:15:15.790
And they've been going
through a mock jury trial.

01:15:15.790 --> 01:15:18.020
And what they now
receive on the scanner

01:15:18.020 --> 01:15:20.690
are the judge's
orders to the jury

01:15:20.690 --> 01:15:22.560
before they go and deliberate.

01:15:22.560 --> 01:15:26.460
First version, the judge says,
remember what you are here for.

01:15:26.460 --> 01:15:27.636
You may have your feelings.

01:15:27.636 --> 01:15:30.260
You may have your feelings about
the person, and what they did,

01:15:30.260 --> 01:15:31.390
or what they didn't do.

01:15:31.390 --> 01:15:35.390
But at the end of the day, your
job as a juror now deliberating

01:15:35.390 --> 01:15:39.440
is simply to decide, was
this law violated or not?

01:15:39.440 --> 01:15:42.060
This is not for you to decide
if it's a good law or not.

01:15:42.060 --> 01:15:45.030
This is simply, was
this law broken?

01:15:45.030 --> 01:15:48.082
Second scenario, the judge
stands there and says, OK,

01:15:48.082 --> 01:15:49.540
as you go and
deliberate, remember,

01:15:49.540 --> 01:15:50.665
of course, what the law is.

01:15:50.665 --> 01:15:53.470
But, remember, at the end of the
day, what is this system about?

01:15:53.470 --> 01:15:56.410
It is about protecting the
weak from the powerful.

01:15:56.410 --> 01:15:59.060
And you are a decision
maker at this point-- two

01:15:59.060 --> 01:15:59.990
totally different.

01:15:59.990 --> 01:16:01.330
One is rule bound.

01:16:01.330 --> 01:16:02.690
On is empathy bound.

01:16:02.690 --> 01:16:06.040
People get the first sets of
rules, cortex is activating.

01:16:06.040 --> 01:16:09.040
Second set of rules, limbic
system is activating.

01:16:09.040 --> 01:16:11.160
So those are some domains
where, in fact, they

01:16:11.160 --> 01:16:13.170
are quite separable.

01:16:13.170 --> 01:16:15.490
What you see,
though, is that there

01:16:15.490 --> 01:16:18.490
are all sorts of domains
in which it is a completely

01:16:18.490 --> 01:16:21.650
ridiculous dichotomy
to make between, oh,

01:16:21.650 --> 01:16:25.280
pure abstract cognitive
decisions, and these messy,

01:16:25.280 --> 01:16:28.100
yucky, emotive limbic
sorts of ones--

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:31.820
instead, tremendous amounts of
interactions between the two.

01:16:31.820 --> 01:16:34.450
One domain where
you see this, which

01:16:34.450 --> 01:16:37.390
is what happens when
you begin to damage

01:16:37.390 --> 01:16:38.510
some of these structures?

01:16:38.510 --> 01:16:41.860
You change the flavor of
the decisions that are made.

01:16:41.860 --> 01:16:44.110
Get people with frontal damage.

01:16:44.110 --> 01:16:46.880
And give them the
runaway trolley problem.

01:16:46.880 --> 01:16:49.330
And they are far more
likely to say, yes,

01:16:49.330 --> 01:16:52.570
it is OK to push
somebody onto the tracks.

01:16:52.570 --> 01:16:56.200
They get a far more
utilitarian decision.

01:16:56.200 --> 01:16:58.770
Equally interesting, and
the same sort of punch line,

01:16:58.770 --> 01:17:01.240
studies where a technique
that's now just being worked out

01:17:01.240 --> 01:17:03.340
called transmagnetic
stimulation,

01:17:03.340 --> 01:17:06.140
were you can
decrease the activity

01:17:06.140 --> 01:17:09.520
of certain cortical regions for
a couple of minutes at a time.

01:17:09.520 --> 01:17:13.260
Turn off one sub region of
the frontal cortex in people,

01:17:13.260 --> 01:17:14.250
in volunteers.

01:17:14.250 --> 01:17:16.890
And in various game theory
games that they're doing,

01:17:16.890 --> 01:17:19.500
they become a lot
more utilitarian.

01:17:19.500 --> 01:17:21.620
They become a lot more selfish.

01:17:21.620 --> 01:17:24.920
So modulating interactions
between there,

01:17:24.920 --> 01:17:27.070
cross talk between the two.

01:17:27.070 --> 01:17:29.530
In some ways the most
interesting demonstration

01:17:29.530 --> 01:17:32.040
for me of the ways in which
these are not separable,

01:17:32.040 --> 01:17:34.580
this thought from
emotion stuff, is

01:17:34.580 --> 01:17:36.790
this really interesting
domain of how

01:17:36.790 --> 01:17:39.360
the human brain does metaphor.

01:17:39.360 --> 01:17:41.350
OK, so we get to symbols.

01:17:41.350 --> 01:17:42.920
We get to abstract things.

01:17:42.920 --> 01:17:46.310
We get into a world where
we have a legal system

01:17:46.310 --> 01:17:49.080
where not only can we judge
that somebody has done something

01:17:49.080 --> 01:17:51.960
wrong to somebody else, if they
have murdered them, or stolen

01:17:51.960 --> 01:17:53.000
their possessions.

01:17:53.000 --> 01:17:55.930
But they can be viewed as having
done something transgressive

01:17:55.930 --> 01:17:59.120
if they've ruined the
reputation of somebody else,

01:17:59.120 --> 01:18:02.980
if they've stolen the ideas
of somebody else, plagiarism.

01:18:02.980 --> 01:18:06.200
This is a very abstract
world of judgments we have.

01:18:06.200 --> 01:18:08.850
These are very symbolic
realms of decision

01:18:08.850 --> 01:18:10.890
making we are often into.

01:18:10.890 --> 01:18:13.330
Yet, we have this
problem that we

01:18:13.330 --> 01:18:17.520
have this very old evolutionary
brain that did not necessarily

01:18:17.520 --> 01:18:20.430
evolve for doing
symbols and metaphors.

01:18:20.430 --> 01:18:22.190
And one of the things
you wind of seeing

01:18:22.190 --> 01:18:25.080
is when the brain
evolved the ability

01:18:25.080 --> 01:18:27.620
to do some of this more
metaphorical stuff,

01:18:27.620 --> 01:18:31.050
it had to make use of the
old circuitry that was there.

01:18:31.050 --> 01:18:32.980
And, thus, what
you wind up seeing

01:18:32.980 --> 01:18:37.350
is very often when dealing
with extremely abstract issues

01:18:37.350 --> 01:18:39.550
of decision making,
we treat some

01:18:39.550 --> 01:18:41.610
of the metaphorical
components as

01:18:41.610 --> 01:18:43.870
if they were absolutely real.

01:18:43.870 --> 01:18:45.720
What would be an
example of this?

01:18:45.720 --> 01:18:50.000
Here's one very cool study
that was done recently.

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:53.170
So your body and your
brain is very wired

01:18:53.170 --> 01:18:55.700
up for doing
temperature regulation.

01:18:55.700 --> 01:18:56.730
Oh, this is hot.

01:18:56.730 --> 01:18:57.660
This is cold.

01:18:57.660 --> 01:18:59.070
These are different
temperatures.

01:18:59.070 --> 01:19:02.330
There's a whole metric,
in temperature-sensitive

01:19:02.330 --> 01:19:03.340
receptors.

01:19:03.340 --> 01:19:05.330
And there's a whole
circuitry thing.

01:19:05.330 --> 01:19:08.080
And it's going about
the very physical task

01:19:08.080 --> 01:19:10.530
in the very real world
of telling something

01:19:10.530 --> 01:19:13.970
about temperature oscillation
of ions, or whatever.

01:19:13.970 --> 01:19:15.550
Get a hold of this study.

01:19:15.550 --> 01:19:17.060
Somebody is coming
up through what

01:19:17.060 --> 01:19:18.940
they believe is some
sort of psych testing

01:19:18.940 --> 01:19:20.510
that they have volunteered for.

01:19:20.510 --> 01:19:22.670
They get in the
elevator to go up.

01:19:22.670 --> 01:19:25.560
And the actual experiment
has started in the elevator.

01:19:25.560 --> 01:19:27.689
Somebody working on the
experiment comes in.

01:19:27.689 --> 01:19:29.480
And they're holding a
whole bunch of books,

01:19:29.480 --> 01:19:30.710
and barely holding on to them.

01:19:30.710 --> 01:19:32.270
And they're having
a cup of something.

01:19:32.270 --> 01:19:34.200
And they ask the person,
can you do me a favor?

01:19:34.200 --> 01:19:35.158
I'm about to drop this.

01:19:35.158 --> 01:19:37.070
Could you just hold
this cup until we get up

01:19:37.070 --> 01:19:38.310
to the fourth floor?

01:19:38.310 --> 01:19:41.100
In one case, the
cup is iced tea.

01:19:41.100 --> 01:19:42.750
The cup is cold.

01:19:42.750 --> 01:19:46.740
In the other case, the
cup is warm tea, warm.

01:19:46.740 --> 01:19:48.720
So the person spends
about 15 seconds

01:19:48.720 --> 01:19:51.489
holding either this cold
cup or this hot cup.

01:19:51.489 --> 01:19:53.030
And the person thanks
them afterward.

01:19:53.030 --> 01:19:54.200
And out they go.

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:56.090
And then they are
asked to evaluate

01:19:56.090 --> 01:19:58.440
the personality of the
person they just interacted

01:19:58.440 --> 01:19:59.560
with in the elevator.

01:19:59.560 --> 01:20:02.430
And hold the warm cup,
and you rate the person

01:20:02.430 --> 01:20:07.220
as having a warmer, more
expressive personality.

01:20:07.220 --> 01:20:09.920
No, no, no, temperature
we're talking about,

01:20:09.920 --> 01:20:12.180
like how fast molecules
are oscillating.

01:20:12.180 --> 01:20:13.830
That's what temperature is.

01:20:13.830 --> 01:20:15.870
Warmth, that's just a metaphor.

01:20:15.870 --> 01:20:17.230
They get intermixed.

01:20:17.230 --> 01:20:19.690
When brains had to invent
dealing with things

01:20:19.690 --> 01:20:23.130
like how warm of a
personality somebody has,

01:20:23.130 --> 01:20:25.330
or even something
as nutty as how warm

01:20:25.330 --> 01:20:27.840
is the color of the
carpeting in this room,

01:20:27.840 --> 01:20:29.540
where are you going to stuff it?

01:20:29.540 --> 01:20:31.930
In some way, it
is hijacking some

01:20:31.930 --> 01:20:34.980
of the far more literal
pathways of storage

01:20:34.980 --> 01:20:36.770
of information in the brain.

01:20:36.770 --> 01:20:39.530
Another example-- here
is a wonderful one.

01:20:39.530 --> 01:20:42.530
We already know that the same
part of the brain, the anterior

01:20:42.530 --> 01:20:45.000
cingulate that will tell
you that your finger was

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:48.390
just poked, is telling you
that somebody else's finger was

01:20:48.390 --> 01:20:48.890
poked.

01:20:48.890 --> 01:20:52.570
You are feeling their pain in
the same part of the brain that

01:20:52.570 --> 01:20:54.990
is doing pain in the
literal sort of way,

01:20:54.990 --> 01:20:58.140
another case of the brain
kind of mixing metaphor

01:20:58.140 --> 01:21:00.120
and symbol with the real thing.

01:21:00.120 --> 01:21:02.850
Here's a particularly
interesting version.

01:21:02.850 --> 01:21:06.620
Go get yourself exposed
to some totally rotting,

01:21:06.620 --> 01:21:09.700
smelly carcass, or
inadvertently take a bite

01:21:09.700 --> 01:21:12.300
into some truly rotten food.

01:21:12.300 --> 01:21:14.890
And you will have an area
of the brain activate called

01:21:14.890 --> 01:21:17.310
the insular cortex.

01:21:17.310 --> 01:21:19.560
And what that does in
every species looked at

01:21:19.560 --> 01:21:24.770
is it processes foul,
disgusting stimuli-- disgusting

01:21:24.770 --> 01:21:27.580
spoiled food, or rotten,
smell all of that.

01:21:27.580 --> 01:21:29.970
That's what the
insular cortex does.

01:21:29.970 --> 01:21:34.190
And, no doubt, there's
tongue receptors telling you

01:21:34.190 --> 01:21:37.220
bacterial loads, or acidity
of this rotten food,

01:21:37.220 --> 01:21:38.420
or some such thing.

01:21:38.420 --> 01:21:40.860
And that's what this
part of the brain does.

01:21:40.860 --> 01:21:42.930
Now, sit down a person.

01:21:42.930 --> 01:21:46.490
And tell them a story of
somebody being totally, totally

01:21:46.490 --> 01:21:51.040
mistreated by somebody powerful,
and some completely exploited

01:21:51.040 --> 01:21:52.480
of horrible circumstance.

01:21:52.480 --> 01:21:55.960
And the insular
cortex will activate.

01:21:55.960 --> 01:21:58.640
Have somebody play some
game with somebody else,

01:21:58.640 --> 01:22:00.560
one of the prisoner's
dilemma type games,

01:22:00.560 --> 01:22:02.851
where the person
totally stabs him

01:22:02.851 --> 01:22:04.850
in the back, the person
they're playing against.

01:22:04.850 --> 01:22:08.280
And gets away with it, and
make a really exploitative,

01:22:08.280 --> 01:22:09.400
rotten gesture.

01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:12.580
And the insular
cortex activates.

01:22:12.580 --> 01:22:15.780
Sit somebody down and
say in the control group,

01:22:15.780 --> 01:22:17.370
tell me about some
event that happened

01:22:17.370 --> 01:22:18.520
when you were growing up.

01:22:18.520 --> 01:22:21.570
Versus the experimental
group, tell me about a time

01:22:21.570 --> 01:22:24.690
when you were growing up that
you did something really awful

01:22:24.690 --> 01:22:26.050
to somebody else.

01:22:26.050 --> 01:22:28.190
And the person describes
that circumstance.

01:22:28.190 --> 01:22:31.160
And the insular
cortex activates.

01:22:31.160 --> 01:22:33.680
What does this part
of the brain do?

01:22:33.680 --> 01:22:36.390
It's saying, oh, yes, this
food is full of maggots

01:22:36.390 --> 01:22:37.940
and does not taste very well.

01:22:37.940 --> 01:22:41.240
But it also does moral disgust.

01:22:41.240 --> 01:22:44.490
When you are feeling
disgusted with how someone

01:22:44.490 --> 01:22:48.190
has been treated, when how you
have been treated it activates.

01:22:48.190 --> 01:22:51.460
When you are having
moral self-disgust

01:22:51.460 --> 01:22:54.000
recounting something
awful you did to somebody,

01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:55.870
this part of the
brain activates.

01:22:55.870 --> 01:22:59.270
My God, don't they realize
up there this is a metaphor?

01:22:59.270 --> 01:23:01.230
You're not really
eating rotten food.

01:23:01.230 --> 01:23:05.080
And every language on
Earth has words referring

01:23:05.080 --> 01:23:07.850
to moral failures
with words denoting

01:23:07.850 --> 01:23:10.780
gustatory, repellent stimuli.

01:23:10.780 --> 01:23:13.200
I am disgusted by what you did.

01:23:13.200 --> 01:23:15.440
The fact that they did
this, when I hear about what

01:23:15.440 --> 01:23:17.200
they did, it makes me nauseous.

01:23:17.200 --> 01:23:19.460
Something about
this smells rotten.

01:23:19.460 --> 01:23:22.430
Every culture has
terms that intermixes

01:23:22.430 --> 01:23:25.880
literal sensory disgust
with moral disgust.

01:23:25.880 --> 01:23:28.810
And what that's telling you
is that when humans came up

01:23:28.810 --> 01:23:31.490
with something as fancy
as moral transgressions,

01:23:31.490 --> 01:23:33.550
where are you going to
stick the sense of outrage

01:23:33.550 --> 01:23:35.425
you feel when there is
a moral transgression?

01:23:35.425 --> 01:23:36.930
I know.

01:23:36.930 --> 01:23:38.730
Let's hijack the part
of the brain that

01:23:38.730 --> 01:23:41.110
tells you you're eating
some rotten food,

01:23:41.110 --> 01:23:43.410
shoehorning into there.

01:23:43.410 --> 01:23:46.430
Now what you see is
it is possible for us

01:23:46.430 --> 01:23:50.090
to begin to confuse on which
level those areas are working.

01:23:50.090 --> 01:23:52.500
Another study, amazing
one a couple of years

01:23:52.500 --> 01:23:54.420
ago-- here's what was
done in the study.

01:23:54.420 --> 01:23:56.030
You take people.

01:23:56.030 --> 01:23:58.030
And you put them
through their paces

01:23:58.030 --> 01:23:59.807
of either telling me
something wonderful

01:23:59.807 --> 01:24:01.390
you did when you
were a kid, something

01:24:01.390 --> 01:24:05.010
neutral, or some moral
transgression you once had.

01:24:05.010 --> 01:24:06.060
Tell me all about it.

01:24:06.060 --> 01:24:08.010
And then afterward,
saying, well,

01:24:08.010 --> 01:24:09.975
thanks for
participating in this.

01:24:09.975 --> 01:24:11.640
And tell you what?

01:24:11.640 --> 01:24:13.240
We can't pay you.

01:24:13.240 --> 01:24:15.930
But we can either
give you this pen set.

01:24:15.930 --> 01:24:18.640
Or we can give you
this nice flash drive.

01:24:18.640 --> 01:24:23.110
Or we can give you this little
soap set of scented soaps,

01:24:23.110 --> 01:24:23.760
or whatever.

01:24:23.760 --> 01:24:27.020
And have people talk about
their moral failings,

01:24:27.020 --> 01:24:30.450
and they're more likely to
choose the soap afterward.

01:24:30.450 --> 01:24:34.340
People want to wash their
hands of their sins.

01:24:34.340 --> 01:24:38.290
And starting with [? pilot ?]
washing his hands of whatever,

01:24:38.290 --> 01:24:42.570
this is in intermixing of
metaphor with reality, showing

01:24:42.570 --> 01:24:44.240
how clearly this was the case.

01:24:44.240 --> 01:24:47.740
Now what they next did in the
study was have people wallow

01:24:47.740 --> 01:24:50.710
in recounting something awful
they had done to somebody else.

01:24:50.710 --> 01:24:53.112
And then they were allowed
to go to the bathroom.

01:24:53.112 --> 01:24:54.570
And I don't quite
remember how they

01:24:54.570 --> 01:24:57.028
did this, if they had cameras
in the bathroom, which I kind

01:24:57.028 --> 01:24:59.980
of suspect they didn't, or if
they weighed the soap afterward

01:24:59.980 --> 01:25:00.550
or something.

01:25:00.550 --> 01:25:03.340
But people who had just gone
through the moral transgression

01:25:03.340 --> 01:25:05.590
recounting were much more
likely to go in the bathroom

01:25:05.590 --> 01:25:07.480
and washed their
hands at that point.

01:25:07.480 --> 01:25:09.310
But now what they
had were people

01:25:09.310 --> 01:25:12.010
who had done the moral
transgression recounting.

01:25:12.010 --> 01:25:14.260
Either they were
given the opportunity

01:25:14.260 --> 01:25:16.910
to wash their hands
afterward of it.

01:25:16.910 --> 01:25:19.920
Or they were not
given the opportunity.

01:25:19.920 --> 01:25:22.780
Now sitting in the
test room, what happens

01:25:22.780 --> 01:25:23.940
is the staged thing.

01:25:23.940 --> 01:25:26.340
One of the people
working on the project

01:25:26.340 --> 01:25:28.550
comes in holding a
whole bunch of books,

01:25:28.550 --> 01:25:30.960
and accidentally drops them.

01:25:30.960 --> 01:25:34.070
And a bunch of pencils
scattered all over the floor.

01:25:34.070 --> 01:25:38.810
If you were allowed to wash your
hands of your metaphorical sins

01:25:38.810 --> 01:25:41.420
in the previous few minutes,
what they showed was

01:25:41.420 --> 01:25:45.750
you were less likely to
jump up and help the person.

01:25:45.750 --> 01:25:48.270
People translating
a sense of being

01:25:48.270 --> 01:25:52.960
morally soiled into being an
imperative of helping somebody

01:25:52.960 --> 01:25:53.550
else.

01:25:53.550 --> 01:25:57.080
Let somebody go wash their hands
of recounting the awful thing

01:25:57.080 --> 01:25:58.820
they did to somebody
else, and they're

01:25:58.820 --> 01:26:01.330
less likely to help
people afterward.

01:26:01.330 --> 01:26:03.280
What I think we're
seeing here is

01:26:03.280 --> 01:26:07.690
this amazing intertwining
of doing some of our most

01:26:07.690 --> 01:26:11.480
abstract judgments, and
decision making, and decisions

01:26:11.480 --> 01:26:14.520
about behaviors or not
where we just got these old,

01:26:14.520 --> 01:26:18.360
ancient, mammalian brains
that those rotten food,

01:26:18.360 --> 01:26:20.150
doesn't do rotten ethics.

01:26:20.150 --> 01:26:22.020
You've got the systems confused.

01:26:22.020 --> 01:26:25.850
What this begins to speak to is
work by very prominent person

01:26:25.850 --> 01:26:28.790
in the field, a guy University
of Virginia Jonathan Haight,

01:26:28.790 --> 01:26:33.360
whose work emphasizes just how
much moral decision making is

01:26:33.360 --> 01:26:37.420
not decision making, how much
it is affective decisions,

01:26:37.420 --> 01:26:41.600
showing first with brain imaging
how often you are getting

01:26:41.600 --> 01:26:46.030
the affective, the limbic,
the disgusted cortical levels

01:26:46.030 --> 01:26:49.310
of response before you
have the decision making.

01:26:49.310 --> 01:26:52.670
Argument being,
there it is affect

01:26:52.670 --> 01:26:55.170
driving the decision making,
rather than the other way

01:26:55.170 --> 01:26:55.850
around.

01:26:55.850 --> 01:26:58.400
But what he also points
out is the frequency

01:26:58.400 --> 01:27:00.270
you give people
scenarios-- and he's

01:27:00.270 --> 01:27:02.320
doing really interesting
work with this-- where

01:27:02.320 --> 01:27:06.190
you give somebody a
scenario where it just

01:27:06.190 --> 01:27:07.580
strikes you as wrong.

01:27:07.580 --> 01:27:10.120
Here are three of
the ones that he

01:27:10.120 --> 01:27:11.720
uses very often in the studies.

01:27:11.720 --> 01:27:15.040
First one, you describe
a pair of siblings.

01:27:15.040 --> 01:27:16.520
They are grown up.

01:27:16.520 --> 01:27:18.539
They are post-reproductive.

01:27:18.539 --> 01:27:19.830
She has gone through menopause.

01:27:19.830 --> 01:27:21.390
He's had a vasectomy, whatever.

01:27:21.390 --> 01:27:25.000
And they are in love, and not
in the platonic sibling way.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:28.260
And they want to have a sexual
incestuous relationship.

01:27:28.260 --> 01:27:31.540
Is it OK for them to do
it completely in private?

01:27:31.540 --> 01:27:34.480
Second scenario-- your
elderly grandmother

01:27:34.480 --> 01:27:37.880
says it is absolutely fine with
her to slap her in the face

01:27:37.880 --> 01:27:38.650
right now.

01:27:38.650 --> 01:27:41.970
Do you feel like it is OK to do?

01:27:41.970 --> 01:27:44.510
Third scenario, one
that he brings up

01:27:44.510 --> 01:27:47.620
having to do with burning
a flag and stomping on it,

01:27:47.620 --> 01:27:50.380
something laden with symbolism,
but at the end of the day

01:27:50.380 --> 01:27:52.800
is nothing more than
just some cloth.

01:27:52.800 --> 01:27:55.330
Another one he brings
up is, you're hungry.

01:27:55.330 --> 01:27:56.840
Your pet has just died.

01:27:56.840 --> 01:27:59.150
Why not cut him up and eat him?

01:27:59.150 --> 01:28:02.900
And in all these cases, what you
have is exactly the responses

01:28:02.900 --> 01:28:04.260
all of you just had in there.

01:28:04.260 --> 01:28:06.350
And these insular,
cortical neurons

01:28:06.350 --> 01:28:08.910
are popping out of people's
ears all over this room.

01:28:08.910 --> 01:28:13.420
And then what he does is say,
well, what's wrong with that?

01:28:13.420 --> 01:28:16.020
And people really
have a hard time

01:28:16.020 --> 01:28:19.770
giving a rational explanation,
this whole framework

01:28:19.770 --> 01:28:22.670
that he has developed, which
most of the imaging research

01:28:22.670 --> 01:28:26.320
agrees with, that people make
their affective decisions long

01:28:26.320 --> 01:28:28.190
before their more
cognitive ones.

01:28:28.190 --> 01:28:31.480
The cognitive ones are catching
up afterward trying to figure

01:28:31.480 --> 01:28:35.400
out, well, why is it so
important that you cannot step

01:28:35.400 --> 01:28:38.090
on some cloth that has
this pattern on it?

01:28:38.090 --> 01:28:40.760
But it's OK to step on
the cloth with-- why

01:28:40.760 --> 01:28:43.900
is that something worth
putting people in jail for?

01:28:43.900 --> 01:28:46.070
It just doesn't feel right.

01:28:46.070 --> 01:28:47.570
And I think what
that has much to do

01:28:47.570 --> 01:28:51.460
with is how much of the
coding of the abstract stuff

01:28:51.460 --> 01:28:54.910
has to be stuffed into ancient
brain pathways that's telling

01:28:54.910 --> 01:28:57.670
you about very cold
things, instead

01:28:57.670 --> 01:29:00.750
of cold personalities,
very disgusting foods

01:29:00.750 --> 01:29:02.760
rather than
disgusting moral acts.

01:29:02.760 --> 01:29:05.880
We are dealing with a very
ancient brain, and one that's

01:29:05.880 --> 01:29:09.460
not very good yet at
separating the limbic world

01:29:09.460 --> 01:29:11.760
from a more cortical one.

01:29:11.760 --> 01:29:14.980
OK, couple more pieces
of this-- final piece

01:29:14.980 --> 01:29:18.840
in terms of making sense of the
neurobiology, which is now you

01:29:18.840 --> 01:29:21.500
look at parts of the
brain when somebody is

01:29:21.500 --> 01:29:22.980
committing an aggressive act.

01:29:22.980 --> 01:29:26.840
And you show neurons
get activated there.

01:29:26.840 --> 01:29:28.230
Well, that's kind
of interesting,

01:29:28.230 --> 01:29:32.740
all sorts of hypothalamus
nuclei, mid-brain, brain stem,

01:29:32.740 --> 01:29:35.910
those reptilian parts of the
brain from the other day.

01:29:35.910 --> 01:29:36.900
You see that happening.

01:29:36.900 --> 01:29:38.941
You say, well, someone
does something aggressive.

01:29:38.941 --> 01:29:40.190
And they activate.

01:29:40.190 --> 01:29:41.580
That seems to be interesting.

01:29:41.580 --> 01:29:42.920
That seems to be pertinent.

01:29:42.920 --> 01:29:45.960
And it winds up being not
pertinent in the slightest,

01:29:45.960 --> 01:29:49.580
because what you see is those
are the same neurons that

01:29:49.580 --> 01:29:52.039
would activate if you are
running for your life.

01:29:52.039 --> 01:29:53.580
Those are the same
neurons that would

01:29:53.580 --> 01:29:56.750
activate if you were running
joyfully to meet someone.

01:29:56.750 --> 01:29:58.330
Those are neurons
that are just doing

01:29:58.330 --> 01:30:01.750
the nuts and bolts sympathetic
nervous system stuff.

01:30:01.750 --> 01:30:03.350
If you were running
for your life,

01:30:03.350 --> 01:30:05.350
or if you were running
towards someone

01:30:05.350 --> 01:30:08.510
you love, and those are totally
different emotional states,

01:30:08.510 --> 01:30:11.070
nonetheless your heart
has to be beating faster.

01:30:11.070 --> 01:30:13.640
And your diaphragm has to be
doing something different.

01:30:13.640 --> 01:30:17.510
These are nonspecific
pathways of activation

01:30:17.510 --> 01:30:19.170
in the sympathetic
nervous system.

01:30:19.170 --> 01:30:22.060
As has been stated, if you are
recording from some of these

01:30:22.060 --> 01:30:24.850
sympathetic nuclei
in the mid-brain,

01:30:24.850 --> 01:30:27.930
if you were recording from them,
you cannot tell the difference

01:30:27.930 --> 01:30:31.320
whether a person has just
murdered someone or just had

01:30:31.320 --> 01:30:32.520
an orgasm.

01:30:32.520 --> 01:30:34.410
In both of those
cases, neurons have

01:30:34.410 --> 01:30:36.420
to be doing very similar things.

01:30:36.420 --> 01:30:40.720
There's a whole realm of
non-specificity to arousal.

01:30:40.720 --> 01:30:43.330
And this brings up a
really important quote,

01:30:43.330 --> 01:30:46.290
and one that I think will run
through all of these aggression

01:30:46.290 --> 01:30:50.470
sections here, a quote
from Elie Wiesel,

01:30:50.470 --> 01:30:53.580
concentration camp survivor,
Nobel Laureate for his writing,

01:30:53.580 --> 01:30:55.930
Elie Wiesel,
extraordinary man, who

01:30:55.930 --> 01:30:59.150
has this famous quote,
which goes as follows.

01:30:59.150 --> 01:31:02.440
The opposite of
love is not hate.

01:31:02.440 --> 01:31:05.950
The opposite of love
is indifference.

01:31:05.950 --> 01:31:07.820
And the way that he
uses it is in sort

01:31:07.820 --> 01:31:09.426
of a historical framework.

01:31:09.426 --> 01:31:10.800
The opposite of
love is not hate.

01:31:10.800 --> 01:31:12.830
The greatest harm
you can do to someone

01:31:12.830 --> 01:31:14.450
who has been a
victim of something

01:31:14.450 --> 01:31:17.230
is to be indifferent
to their history,

01:31:17.230 --> 01:31:20.596
to deny that it has happened,
to see it not be an imperative

01:31:20.596 --> 01:31:22.720
to make sure it never
happens to anyone else again,

01:31:22.720 --> 01:31:23.880
et cetera, et cetera.

01:31:23.880 --> 01:31:26.470
The opposite of hate
is indifference.

01:31:26.470 --> 01:31:29.770
Applied to physiology here,
it is absolutely the case.

01:31:29.770 --> 01:31:32.240
When you look at what the
sympathetic nervous system is

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:35.290
doing, when you look at
some of the stress hormones,

01:31:35.290 --> 01:31:37.750
love and hate are not
opposites in the slightest.

01:31:37.750 --> 01:31:40.330
They are physiologically
very, very similar.

01:31:40.330 --> 01:31:42.390
What I think that
also tells you is

01:31:42.390 --> 01:31:45.580
how readily some humans
psychopathologically

01:31:45.580 --> 01:31:47.380
can confuse the two states.

01:31:47.380 --> 01:31:48.960
When you look at
some of these brain

01:31:48.960 --> 01:31:52.160
stem hindbrain spinal
areas during these acts,

01:31:52.160 --> 01:31:53.820
love and hate are not opposites.

01:31:53.820 --> 01:31:56.270
They are very related
to each other.

01:31:56.270 --> 01:32:00.270
OK, jumping forward in the last
couple of minutes, what we now

01:32:00.270 --> 01:32:03.040
have is looking at
what hormones are doing

01:32:03.040 --> 01:32:05.830
to this-- hormones in terms
of the short-term hormonal

01:32:05.830 --> 01:32:09.000
environment, not early in
life, the short-term hormonal

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:09.700
environment.

01:32:09.700 --> 01:32:12.130
And what we have to deal
with, of course, instantly

01:32:12.130 --> 01:32:13.930
if we're going to
bring up hormones is,

01:32:13.930 --> 01:32:16.370
so what's the deal
with testosterone?

01:32:16.370 --> 01:32:19.340
What does testosterone
have to do with aggression?

01:32:19.340 --> 01:32:22.480
Why is it that in virtually
every species out there,

01:32:22.480 --> 01:32:25.490
males are more aggressive
than females, males have more

01:32:25.490 --> 01:32:27.140
testosterone than females do?

01:32:27.140 --> 01:32:29.720
All you need to do to make
sense of this whole section

01:32:29.720 --> 01:32:32.410
here is take everything
from last week concerning

01:32:32.410 --> 01:32:34.890
testosterone and sexual
behavior and just

01:32:34.890 --> 01:32:38.150
substitute aggressive
behavior for sexual behavior.

01:32:38.150 --> 01:32:39.980
It's the same exact rules.

01:32:39.980 --> 01:32:43.560
Yes, testosterone is required
for the full expression

01:32:43.560 --> 01:32:46.430
of aggressive behavior
in males of most species.

01:32:46.430 --> 01:32:47.470
How do you tell?

01:32:47.470 --> 01:32:50.160
Subtract it out, the
castration stuff.

01:32:50.160 --> 01:32:53.690
After castration, do levels
of aggression go down to zero?

01:32:53.690 --> 01:32:57.620
No, same thing as last
week, the more prior

01:32:57.620 --> 01:33:00.520
experience one has
being aggressive,

01:33:00.520 --> 01:33:02.260
the less of a drop
in aggression there

01:33:02.260 --> 01:33:05.290
is after testosterone
levels are removed.

01:33:05.290 --> 01:33:09.600
Put back 100% the normal levels,
aggression is reinstated.

01:33:09.600 --> 01:33:13.710
Put back 10% the normal levels,
reinstated to the same extent,

01:33:13.710 --> 01:33:18.070
200%, same extent, same
exact rule-- testosterone

01:33:18.070 --> 01:33:21.140
is needed for the normal
expression of behavior.

01:33:21.140 --> 01:33:24.490
But it is not necessary
or sufficient.

01:33:24.490 --> 01:33:26.600
And your brain,
your limbic system,

01:33:26.600 --> 01:33:28.730
can't tell the
difference between

01:33:28.730 --> 01:33:32.290
moderate, medium, and very
high levels of testosterone.

01:33:32.290 --> 01:33:34.840
There is no way you could
look at an individual's

01:33:34.840 --> 01:33:36.820
testosterone levels,
and because it's

01:33:36.820 --> 01:33:39.220
two units higher than
it was last week,

01:33:39.220 --> 01:33:41.640
or higher than the person
sitting next to them, to make

01:33:41.640 --> 01:33:45.260
any sort of prediction about who
is going to be more aggressive.

01:33:45.260 --> 01:33:47.990
When you see a correlation
between the levels

01:33:47.990 --> 01:33:50.660
of aggression and
levels of testosterone,

01:33:50.660 --> 01:33:54.400
it's the behavior driving the
testosterone, not the other way

01:33:54.400 --> 01:33:55.680
around.

01:33:55.680 --> 01:33:57.870
How does this translate
into physiology?

01:33:57.870 --> 01:34:01.190
Here's one example of
this in terms of studies.

01:34:01.190 --> 01:34:03.520
Take five rhesus monkey
males-- and this was

01:34:03.520 --> 01:34:05.120
a classic study that was done.

01:34:05.120 --> 01:34:07.780
Put them together, and they
form a dominance hierarchy.

01:34:07.780 --> 01:34:09.630
Number run beats
two through five,

01:34:09.630 --> 01:34:11.800
number two beats three
through five, so on.

01:34:11.800 --> 01:34:15.220
Take number three and pump
him up with testosterone.

01:34:15.220 --> 01:34:18.240
Pump him up with insane
amounts of testosterone.

01:34:18.240 --> 01:34:22.800
And what you will see is he will
now be involved in more fights.

01:34:22.800 --> 01:34:25.600
Does that mean that number
three is now threatening

01:34:25.600 --> 01:34:27.420
number two and number one?

01:34:27.420 --> 01:34:30.570
Absolutely not, what's
going on, number three

01:34:30.570 --> 01:34:34.280
is being a nightmare to
numbers four and five.

01:34:34.280 --> 01:34:37.270
Is testosterone
changing the structure

01:34:37.270 --> 01:34:38.780
of aggression in this group?

01:34:38.780 --> 01:34:43.670
No, it's exaggerating the
pre-existing social structure.

01:34:43.670 --> 01:34:46.360
What testosterone
does is modulate.

01:34:46.360 --> 01:34:47.660
It amplifies.

01:34:47.660 --> 01:34:51.510
It does not turn on a
